<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Wants End to Gold Sales: Zuma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zuma told a press conference here that many developing
countries, which have gold production as their economic backbone,
have suffered a great deal after the gold price plunged to a
20-year record low.
</P>
<P>
She said that not only the gold producing countries were the
victims of gold sales but also the countries exporting gold miners
were dealt a heavy blow.
</P>
<P>
Zuma was speaking after the end of a two-day ministerial
meeting of the Southern African Development Community (SADC) which
preceded a SADC summit scheduled for August 18.
</P>
<P>
She said the 14 SADC ministers discussed, among other issues,
the negative impact of gold sales on SADC gold producing
countries.
</P>
<P>
The gold price dipped to around 255 dollars an ounce from about
290 dollars after Britain announced its plan in May to sell part
of its gold reserves. The International Monetary Fund (IMF)
announced later that it also planned to sell 5 million to 10
million ounces of gold for funding its plan to relieve the poorest
countries of their debt burden.
</P>
<P>
Zuma noted that the IMF plan, if carried out, would hurt the
countries it intended to help rather than assisting them.
</P>
<P>
She urged the IMF to find other alternatives to fund its plan
for debt relief.
</P>
<P>
A number of SADC countries are gold producers. but since the
plunge of gold price, the countries as well as their neighbors
that rely on labor export for currency remittance have lost
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
Zuma disclosed that the upcoming SADC summit will devote its
attention to gold sales, saying, "a position has to be adopted on
the issue." 
</P>
</TEXT>
