<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo Rebels Not Invited to SADC Meeting: Zuma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There have been reports in the local media that the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) had invited Congo rebels to
Maputo on the sidelines of a SADC summit to sign a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said in response to a related question that she had no
information that Congo rebels had been invited.
</P>
<P>
She said the rebels would not come and there would be no
signing of the treaty during the summit.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said the two-day SADC ministerial meeting mainly dealt
with economic and trade issues. Regional conflicts, she said, were
left for the heads of state when they meet here on August 18.
</P>
<P>
She said the Zambian president would deliver a special report
on the situation in Congo at the summit.
</P>
<P>
The Tutsi-led rebels are trying to topple Congolese President
Laurent Kabila's government. On July 10, Kabila and his allies --
Angola, Namibia, Zimbabwe -- signed a peace agreement, as did the
backers of the rebels, Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
However, the main rebel movement, the Congolese Rally for
Democracy (RCD), has declined to sign amid a leadership row that
has split the movement into two.
</P>
<P>
Zuma hinted that it would take time to end conflicts in the
region, including the one in Congo. She went to the Congo earlier
this month to narrow the gap between the two rival factions but
returned empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said people expected the SADC to help end regional
conflicts quickly but "conflicts cannot be ended as quickly as
they are started". 
</P>
</TEXT>
