<HEADLINE> Chiluba to Present Report on Congo to SADC Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign Minister
Nkosazana Zuma said here Sunday that Zambian President F. Chiluba
will present a report on the Congo peace process to the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) summit Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zuma, who is also chairperson of the SADC council of minister,
said at a press briefing that Chiluba was appointed to deal with
the Congo issue at the last SADC summit in Mauritius last
September.
</P>
<P>
The president is in charge of that process with the help of
other countries, she said, adding that as recently as this week
the president sent his minister to Kisangani in northeastern Congo
to identify the process.
</P>
<P>
The minister will report to President Chiluba and the president
will present an appropriate report on the Congo issue to the
summit as required by the last summit meeting, said Zuma.
</P>
<P>
The prospect of the peace process in the vast central African
country became rosy when a cease-fire agreement was reached in
Zambian capital Lusaka on July 10 by the six countries directly
involved in the Congo conflict.
</P>
<P>
However, the Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD), one major
rebel group in the Congo, has failed to sign the accord due to its
internal dispute over leadership, which has endangered the fragile
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
In response to a report in the Noticias newspaper here Sunday,
Zuma said that she doesn't expect the Congolese rebels to come to
the Mozambican capital.
</P>
<P>
The mozambican paper quoted Zuma's spokesperson Vincent
Hlonguane as saying that the rebels in the Congo were coming to
sign the Lusaka cease- fire agreement in maputo where the SADC
summit will take place Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said that her spokesperson did not say that.
</P>
<P>
SADC Executive Secretary Kaire Mbuende, who was sitting beside
Zuma, also said that he doesn't expect the Congolese rebels to
come.
</P>
<P>
However, Zuma expressed optimism toward an end to the
one-year-old Congo war, though she could not give a deadline.
</P>
<P>
"The war has to end," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
But the minister, snapping her fingers, noted that a war is
easy to start but not so easy to end.
</P>
<P>
She said that the security issues were not supposed to be
addressed by the ministers and they will be discussed at the
summit of heads of state on the cease-fire. enditem

NNNN
04:31 04:31 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
