<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Orders Re-examination of Development Priorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak on Sunday took a preliminary step toward a possible change
in the priority status Jewish settlements have enjoyed, ordering
a committee to restart examination of the issue.
</P>
<P>
Barak announced at a cabinet meeting that the
Directors-General Committee on National Preferential Development
Areas would resume operations, according to a cabinet statement.
</P>
<P>
The priority status of Jewish settlements in national
development was canceled by former prime minister Yitzhak Rabin
but restored by Barak's hard-line predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians regard the more than 150 settlements
scattering in the West Bank and Gaza as illegal and an obstacle
to their aspiration to build an independent state, calling on
Israeli governments to remove all the settlements.
</P>
<P>
After trouncing Netanyahu in the May election, Barak has
undertaken not to build new Jewish settlements and not to
dismantle existing ones in West Bank and Gaza before Israel and
the Palestinians enter the final-status talks, during which the
final borders will be drawn.
</P>
<P>
During his election campaign, Barak has promised to stop
the flowing of millions of shekels to settlements and redirect
them to the fields of education and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
New Industry and Trade Minister Ran Cohen from the left-wing
Meretz party ordered last month to suspend all applications for
industrial investment subsidies in Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
The freezing of approvals for factory subsidies beyond the
Green Line, which divides Israel and the territories it seized
in the 1967 war, will be in effect until the government
completes examination of its priority in national development
areas.
</P>
<P>
Israeli governments offer varying levels of capital spending
aid to new industrial or tourism enterprises in areas designated
national development zones.
</P>
<P>
During the three years of Netanyahu's government, about 240
million U.S. dollars of new investments were channeled to in West
Bank and Gaza settlements.
</P>
<P>
Of the investments, the government had provided subsidies
totaling 300 million shekels (some 73 million U.S. dollars). But
Cohen said the money was inappropriately allocated because the
settlements did not suffer high unemployment compared to many
towns inside the Green Line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
