<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabweans to Attend Hawaii Youth Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Peace Child Zimbabwe, a
non-governmental organization that caters for the youth Sunday
said it has selected 12 youths to represent Zimbabwe at the
Millennium Young People's Congress in Hawaii in October.
</P>
<P>
National Coordinator Leornard Kachingwe told the Zimbabwe News
Agency that the youth would be accompanied by poet Albert Nyathi's
renowned dance group Ibongi.
</P>
<P>
He said Ibongi was the only group selected from Africa to
perform at the worldwide youth congress.
</P>
<P>
The delegation from Zimbabwe would be made up of 22 people
including the 12 youths and members of Ibongi.
</P>
<P>
The youths were selected by a steering committee in Britain
after sending their pictures, poems and other materials.
</P>
<P>
Peace Child Zimbabwe is an affiliate of Peace Child
International.
</P>
<P>
Kachingwe said, "The congress will discuss priorities for the
youth in the next century. It will be a platform for them to tell
the world what they want to see happening in the millennium."
</P>
<P>
He said the materials from Zimbabwe had been rated of the
highest quality by the selection committee in London.
</P>
<P>
Before the selection, the youth organization had advertized in
newspapers and on radio, inviting people between 12 and 25 years
to send in their ideas for consideration.
</P>
<P>
The congress, funded by the United Nations, would be a
follow-up to the Rio Earth Summit Agenda 21 where world leaders
agreed to priorities issues affecting the youth.
</P>
<P>
Kachingwe said the congress would give Zimbabwean youth an
insight into other youths' vision for the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
He said the youths would compile a book containing resolutions
of the congress to be presented to world leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
