<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African FM Pours Cold Water on Freedom of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign Minister
Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma Sunday poured cold water on the notion of
freedom of movement within the Southern African Development
Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
addressing reporters in Maputo, Zuma, who also chairs the SADC
council of ministers, said that "freedom of movement does not take
place overnight."
</P>
<P>
"It's an on-going discussion and an aim toward which SADC is
working," she said, adding that "talking about an object doesn't
mean it must happen today."
</P>
<P>
The South African minister said this in response to a question
raised by the Mozambican News Agency (AIM) in the context of
recent repatriations of Mozambicans from three other SADC members
namely South Africa, Zimbabwe and Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
She said that the ministers have adopted two draft protocols,
one on wildlife conservation and law enforcement, the other on
health, as well as a declaration on productivity.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will submit to the Wednesday summit for
signatures of these two protocols.
</P>
<P>
So far, nine protocols on immunities and privileges, shared
watercourse systems, transport communications and meteorology,
energy, combating illicit drug trafficking, trade, education and
training, mining and tourism, have been signed by member states,
according to SADC executive secretary Kaire Mbuende.
</P>
<P>
Zuma was optimistic as the crucial trade protocol aiming to
achieve a free trade area in the southern Africa has been ratified
by six SADC member states. They are Botswana, Malawi, Mauritius,
Namibia, Tanzania and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
But three more states are needed to ratify the trade protocol
to enable it to come into force.
</P>
<P>
The South African Foreign Minister was confident that more SADC
members would sign by the end of the year and the tax reduction
would begin in next January as scheduled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
