<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Putin Says No Need for Emergency Rule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Acting Russian Prime Minister
Vladimir Putin reiterated Sunday that there is no need to impose
an emergency rule in Russia.
</P>
<P>
"No internal political conditions call for introducing a state
of emergency in the Russian territory," Putin told the Vesti
television program.
</P>
<P>
"A special rule might be introduced" in the fighting zone in
North Caucasus, he said. "The local authorities have clearly
ceased to function there."
</P>
<P>
Russia's federal and local troops are fighting Islamic
militants that seized several villages over a week ago in
Daghestan, a republic bordering the breakaway Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
In Chechnya itself, President Aslan Maskhadov has decided to
impose a 30-day state of emergency starting Monday, in an apparent
response to Putin's earlier indication that the campaign against
the militants might be extended to inside Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
"We will resolve the (Dagestani) problem without any emergency
steps," Putin said, adding that the militants "would either be
eliminated or ousted from Dagestan." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
