<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's CPI up by 0.3 percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Consumer Price Index
(CPI) rose 0.3 percent in July to stand at 105.1 points, a little
higher than projected, the Central Bureau of Statistics reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The CPI has risen 6.3 percent since July last year.
</P>
<P>
During the first seven months of this year, the sectors that saw
index increase are health by 3.7 percent, education and culture by
2.6 percent, and foodstuffs by 1.6 percent, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The housing sector saw its index up by 1.5 percent in July,
contributing 0.3 percent to the general CPI, reflecting a revival
in the housing market, the figure showed.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate for this year was targeted at 4 percent and
the new government under Prime Minister Ehud Barak last week set
an annual inflation target of 3 to 4 percent for the year 2000
and 2001.
</P>
<P>
Economists here said Bank of Israel Governor Jacob Frenkel is
unlikely to reduce interest rates further this month because he
has insisted on his tight financial policy in order to keep a low
inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate stands at 11 percent after being cut twice
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
