<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Explosion in Israel Suspected of Being </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli police began an
investigation Sunday into a bomb explosion in the northern
coastal city of Netanya which they suspected to be a foiled major
terror attack, Israel television reports said.
</P>
<P>
Before the bomb exploded outside an office building in the
morning, the police spotted two men carrying suspicious packages,
the reports said. The men headed into downtown before police
could question them.
</P>
<P>
Security officials were quoted as saying that the suspects
might have intended to conduct the explosion in heavy traffic
areas but had to dump the bomb after realizing that they had been
spotted.
</P>
<P>
No casualties and only light property damage were caused by the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security facilities have warned that there might be an
increase in militant attacks since Israel and the Palestinians
are resuming the peace process stalled under former Israeli
prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Resistance Movement, or Hamas, which is opposed to
the Israeli-Palestinian peace making, has said that it will
resume militant attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has carried out several major suicide bombings in Israel
since 1993, when the historic Oslo accords between Israel and the
Palestinians were signed.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Police Chief Yehuda Wilk said last week that Israeli
security forces foiled several attack attempts in the last few
months.
</P>
<P>
A 23-year-old Palestinian from the West Bank town of Bethlehem
rammed his car twice into a group of Israeli soldiers last Tuesday
at an intersection about 30 miles southwest of Jerusalem, injuring
seven before being shot to death by Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
But the new Israeli government of Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) have taken careful
steps to prevent the peacemaking from being derailed by the
attack.
</P>
<P>
Barak's envoy Gilad Sher and senior Palestinian negotiator
Saeb Erekat met Sunday afternoon on the Palestinian side of the
Erez border crossing to continue their efforts to resolve the
differences over the timetable of implementation of the Wye
Memorandum.
</P>
<P>
The two had failed to achieve a breakthrough in their previous
meetings held in Jerusalem Wednesday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Since taking office on July 6, Barak has promised to carry out
the Wye agreement, signed and then frozen by his hard-line
predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu last year, but proposed some
changes to the accord, under which Israel has to hand over 13
percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have reluctantly accepted his proposal to
begin implementation of the agreement at the beginning of
September and carry out the second stage of troop withdrawal on
October 1.
</P>
<P>
Barak told a cabinet meeting Sunday that he had ordered the
Israeli army to prepare for the Wye implementation.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides have been at odds over Barak's proposal to
postpone the final stage of the agreement until February 2000,
when the final-status talks dealing with thorny issues like
Jerusalem and settlements are supposed to have been well under way.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have turned down the idea, calling on Barak
to complete the implementation of the final stage by mid-November
in line with the original timetable of the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
Barak said Sunday that he hoped the two sides would iron out
their differences on the timetable within 10 days, before
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright starts a visit to the
region.
</P>
<P>
Albright had originally scheduled her visit for mid-August,
which would have started Sunday, with an aim of ensuring the
Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations are on the track and
trying to restart the frozen Israeli-Syrian talks.
</P>
<P>
But she postponed the visit by two weeks at the request of
Barak, who wants Washington to give him more time to resolve his
difference with Arafat by themselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
