<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Calls for Stronger Role of Arab League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin
Hussein Sunday called on the Arab League to enhance its role as an
international organization to safeguard Arab interests in
regional and world affairs.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal during his meeting with visiting Arab League
Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid who arrived in Amman
earlier in the day to attend the opening ceremony of the ninth
Pan-Arab Games.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders discussed the inter-Arab relations and the
latestest developments in the Middle East peace process, Jordan's
official news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah stressed the need to revive united Arab actions in
world affairs and to promote inter-Arab relations, Petra said.
</P>
<P>
Meguid praised Abdullah for his positive role in uniting the
Arab world and consolidating ties of cooperation among Arab
countries, Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
"Jordan has been always in the forefront of the Arab states
advocating a greater role for the Arab League," said secretary
general of the Cairo-based league.
</P>
<P>
Meguid will deliver a speech at the opening ceremony of the
ninth Pan-Arab Games to start in Amman Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
Some 4,600 athletes from 21 Arab countries will take part in
the two-week event, the largest sports gathering of Arab
countries in the modern history.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is expected to send a delegation headed by a minister
to the opening ceremony, but its athletes will boycott the games
to protest the participation of their Iraqi counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Jordan had failed to persuade Kuwait to send its athletes to
the games which Amman hoped to use as a showcase for Arab
solidarity.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Kuwait and Iraq remained soured since the
1990 Gulf crisis which was triggered by the invasion of the tiny
gulf emirate by Iraqi troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
