<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 29 Massacred in Southern Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-nine people were massacred
assumably by Islamic militants in southern Algeria Saturday night,
according to reports from Algiers.
</P>
<P>
Algerian security services said that the massacre, the
deadliest since President Abdelaziz Bouteflika took office in
April, took place in a village called Beni Ounif located in the
region of Bechar, 750 kilometers southwest of Algiers.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers and rescuers were dispatched to the scene of the
killings to help the families of the killed and the injured, said
the Algerian authorities.
</P>
<P>
The killings also raised fear that massacres could resume in
Algeria after an half-year relative peace.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the southern area of Algeria, where the newest
massacres took place, was relatively free from violence during the
war between government forces and Islamic militants which was
concentrated in the east and west parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Sporadic attacks against both military personnel and civilians
by Islamists have been resuming for several weeks, after President
Bouterflika announced on August 1 that the nation will hold a
referendum on adopting a "civil concord law" on September 16.
</P>
<P>
At least 17 Algerian soldiers were killed in the past one week
in several attacks attributed to Islamists in Kabylie, east
Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian army began last Thursday a major offensive against
the Islamic guerrillas in Kabylie, a mountainous region inhabited
by the minority Berbers.
</P>
<P>
Two most radical Islamic groups of Algeria, the Salafist Group
for the Prediction and Combat (GSPC) and the Armed Islamic Group
(GIA), have rejected the proposal by the government on national
reconciliation after an estimated 100,000 were killed in seven
years of war since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Another armed Islamic group, the Islamic Salvation Army, has
accepted the government proposal, which includes the pardoning of
Islamists except those who have committed killings, attacks which
have handicapped people permanently, and rapes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
