<HEADLINE> 3 Iraqi Civilians Injured in U.S. Air Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Three Iraqi civilians were
injured in U.S.-British warplanes' attacks on a mosque
in northern Iraq on Sunday, an Iraqi military spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 10:15 (0615 GMT) nine formations
of enemy warplanes coming from Turkish airspace violated northern
Iraqi airspace over Dohuk, Neineva and Erbil provinces.
</P>
<P>
These warplanes attacked a mosque near Saddam Dam in Neineva
province, leading to the destruction of the mosque and injuries
of three civilians, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Iraqi anti-aircraft units fired back
at the enemy planes and repulsed them to their base in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He said that at 11:00 (0700 GMT) 10 formations of U.S.
and British warplanes coming from the Saudi and Kuwaiti bases
violated southern Iraqi airspace over Basra, Thi-Qar, Muthana and
Misan provinces.
</P>
<P>
These enemy warplanes bombed some civilian installations in
the region, he said, adding that Iraqi anti-aircraft units
repulsed the enemy planes.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's airstrikes against Iraq, U.S. and
British warplanes have made 11,375 sorties over the two no-fly
zones in Iraq, and have been regularly attacking Iraqi civilian
facilities and military sites.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed on Iraq by the U.S.-led
western allies following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed
aim of protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite
Muslims in the south from attacks by Iraqi government troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
