<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Prolonged Angolan Civil War (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Angola civil war will be
among the topics to dominate the political agenda at the annual
Southern African Development Community (SADC) summit in Maputo
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It is shocking, but true, that some Angolans have never known
peace in their country.
</P>
<P>
The civil war has been going on since 1975 immediately after
the country gained independence from Portugal, and a set of
international factors have sustained the conflict ever since.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, Angola became the battlefield of the cold war
between the United States on the one side and the Soviet-Cuban
alliance on the other.
</P>
<P>
A semblance of hope came in the early 1990s when Angolans,
including the rebels, went to the polls.
</P>
<P>
However, hope was soon dashed when the National Union for Total
 Independence of Angola (UNITA) resumed fighting after losing the
election.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the U.N. has imposed sanctions on the UNITA,
including prohibition of its trade in diamonds, the sale of
petroleum products and arms to the rebel movement, and freezing
UNITA's assets abroad. The sanctions also banned foreign travel by
UNITA officials and adult members of their families.
</P>
<P>
A peace agreement known as the Lusaka accord, was cobbled
together in 1994. The U.N. and three world powers, Portugal, the
former colonizer, the U.S. and Russia, acted as guarantors of the
deal.
</P>
<P>
Subsequent to the peace deal, the UNITA was recognized as a
political party and its leader Jonas Savimbi obtained special
status with numerous rights and privileges.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA which controlled 335 cities before 1994 handed some
260 back to the control of the government in Luanda led by
President Jose Eduardo Dos Santos.
</P>
<P>
Though a unity government was formed, with several UNITA-led
ministries, parliamentary deputies and ambassadorships, Savimbi
never returned to Luanda to take up his position as the opposition
leader, citing security concerns as the reasons.
</P>
<P>
A group of UNITA ministers and parliamentarians formed a
splinter movement for renewal, the Renovation Commission of the
UNITA in September 1998. And later the Angolan government declared
Savimbi to be a criminal and said it would only negotiate with
the renewal UNITA. But Savimbi was still very much in control of
the rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
At the last SADC summit in Mauritius last September, regional
leaders declared UNITA chief Jonas Savimbi as "a war criminal" to
be hunted down.
</P>
<P>
A full-blown civil war renewed in the southern African
countries when the government troops and the UNITA forces were
involved in fierce fightings in central highlands in December last
year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Presidents Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe, Sam
Nujoma of Namibia and Laurent Kabila of the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) met in Luanda and formed an alliance with Dos Santos
against the UNITA rebels.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state resolved to use "all possible measures" to
help Dos Santos's government.
</P>
<P>
However, so far, "all possible measures" has excluded
Zimbabwean and Namibian military involvement because they already
have thousands of troops in the Congo, propping up Kabila's
regime, and the troops are unlikely to be home before Christmas if
everything goes well after the cease-fire pact was signed in
Zambia on July 10. Considering the U.N. as a shield for the
rebellious movement, the Angolan government demanded a pull-out of
the U.N. Observer Mission in Angola (MONUA) last January, When the
government troops encountered some setbacks in battlefields in the
central provinces of Huambo and Bie. The U.N. mission formally
pulled out from the war-torn country on March 1 this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Foresees Deal Within 10 Days over Wye </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak said Sunday he is hopeful that Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators will reach an agreement in 10 days on the way of
implementing the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
"There is some kind of chance during the next 10 days that
some kind of agreement will be formulated on the manners in which
the Wye accord will be implemented," Israel Radio quoted Barak as
telling a weekly cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Barak's envoy Gilad Sher and senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb
Erekat resumed their talks Sunday afternoon on the Palestinian
side of the Erez border crossing to resolve differences on the
timetable for the Wye implementation.
</P>
<P>
The two had met Wednesday and Saturday in Jerusalem, but to little
avail.
</P>
<P>
Since taking office early last month, Barak has promised to
implement the Wye accord signed and then frozen by his hard-line
predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu last year, but he also proposed
some changes to the implementation of the agreement, which calls
on Israel to hand over 13 percent of the West Bank to the
Palestinians in three stages.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have reluctantly accepted his proposal to
restart the timetable of the Wye agreement on September 1 and
begin to carry out the second stage of troop withdrawal on October
1.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu carried out the first stage late last year before
halting the agreement.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides have been at odds over Barak's suggestion to
postpone the implementation of the third stage of troop withdrawal
until February 2000, when the final-status talks dealing with
thorny issues like Jerusalem and Jewish settlements are supposed
to have been well under way.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians demand that the third stage be carried out by
mid-November in line with the original timetable of Wye.
</P>
<P>
Barak reported to the cabinet meeting that he has instructed
the army to begin preparations for resuming implementation of the
Wye accord on September 1 and carrying out the second stage of
troop withdrawal on October 1, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio reported earlier that Barak and Palestinian National
Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat will hold a summit meeting this
week if the negotiators reach agreement on a timetable. However,
the Palestinians have denied that such a summit has been
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that Barak proposed the 10-day time limit
for the negotiations because he wanted to iron out his differences
with Arafat before a planned visit to the region by U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Albright originally scheduled her visit in mid-August, which
would have started Sunday, with an aim of ensuring the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks are on the track and restarting
the frozen negotiations between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
But she has postponed the visit by two weeks at the request of
Barak, who wants Washington to play a less direct role in the
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Prolonged Angolan Civil War (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dos Santos sacked the UNITA members of government as part of
his frustration with its's continued violation of the peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA has consistently called for fresh negotiations with
the Angolan government, which Luanda has rejected.
</P>
<P>
Angolan Foreign Minister Joao Miranda said recently that
Savimbi "has never accepted the implementation of any accord."
</P>
<P>
In any event, the Angolan government has no intention of
resuming talks with Savimbi, suspecting whether he would accept
them at a time when the rebel leader is "committed to seizing
power by force of arms."
</P>
<P>
Recently, the U.N. committee overseeing the enforcement of
sanctions against the UNITA has enlisted the cooperation of a
broad coalition of interests, including the global diamond
industry, to enforce the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the committee, Robert Fowler, assured that the goal
in such broad diplomatic effort is to ensure that the UNITA goes
back to dialog in peacefully resolving the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Angolan Ambassador to the United Nations, Afonso Van Dunem said
early this month that his government has made a "positive
endorsement" for the U. N. presence in the southwest African
country.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador announced that the Angolan government delivered
a letter Wednesday to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
"expressly notifying the decision of the government."
</P>
<P>
The ambassador stressed that the Angolan government has been
in favor of a "not so big" U.N. presence, in correspondence with
the reality of the situation in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.N. expressed a will to maintain a mediatory
organization in Angola.
</P>
<P>
But the Angolan government insisted that this kind of agency
should be established in New York, where the U.N. is
headquartered.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique and Zambia have been accused of transporting arms to
the UNITA rebels, which both nations denied. Angola's accusation
has somehow soured the relations between Luanda and Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal Mocumbi denied that
Mozambique's northern port of Nacala is being used for clandestine
military supplies to Angolan rebel movement UNITA.
</P>
<P>
Mocumbi declined to comment on the arrest warrant the Angolan
authorities have issued for Savimbi, nor on possible attempts to
send troops from other SADC countries to assist the embattled
Angolan government.
</P>
<P>
"Mozambique supports all efforts to allow Angola to regain
peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the United Nations Development Program (UNDP)
report on 1999 human development index of 174 countries in the
world, Angola ranks 160th, down from the 157th position last
year, largely due to the ravaging civil war.
</P>
<P>
Angolan Minister of Assistance and Resettlement Albino Muisngo
said that the country is in need of about 200 million u.s. dollars
in humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan currency readjusted kwanza depreciated from 196,916
to one U. S. dollar in September, 1997 to 257,128 to one dollar.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Program estimated that Angola needs 13,000 tons
of food aid per month to feed its nearly two million displaced
people.
</P>
<P>
Due to the ravaging civil war, the government's anti-polio
campaign could not be effectively carried out. If the war is not
stopped soon, the southwestern african country will be unable to
meet the world health organization's target of wiping out the
childhood disease by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Angola as well as the whole southern Africa can ill-afford the
lingering conflicts and insecurity in the region.
</P>
<P>
The regional leaders to gather in Maputo Wednesday are expected
to act in the spirit of true African solidarity to further their
efforts to abandon destructive wars in the region.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that the Angolan crisis will not be
resolved militarily but diplomatically through peaceful and
political means, though the leaders at the Maputo summit will
probably reinforce their support for a peace agreement in Angola
with the threat of resorting to military force to help Luanda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
