<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Become Sugar Exporter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia will export sugar
in 1999/ 2000 for the first time, the state-owned Sugar Industry
Support Center announced.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia is planning to export up to 100,000 tons of sugar to
the world market in 1999/2000 and earn around 22 million U.S.
dollars in foreign currency, Shewaferaw Girma of the center said
early this week.
</P>
<P>
The export were made possible by the opening earlier this year
of the country's 4th sugar factory at Finchaa in western Ethiopia,
Shewaferaw said.
</P>
<P>
The latest built sugar factory was designed to produce 85,000
tons of sugar a year.
</P>
<P>
According to Shewaferaw, Ethiopia will produce around 275,000
tons of sugar in the coming season from 23,500 hectares of
irrigated cane-field.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia is one of the lowest levels of per capita sugar
consumption in the world, at just 3.5 kgs per head per year,
against an average of 20 kgs per head in sub-Saharan Africa,
government figures show.
</P>
<P>
The start of sugar exports is expected to help to diversify
Ethiopia's economy away from its dependence on coffee, which
curently accounts for around 60 percent of foreign currency
earnings.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia did not get acquaintance with sugar until the Italians
intruded the country from 1936 to 1941. Before sugar was
introduced, Ethiopians drank sugarless coffee or even spiced it
with a pinch of salt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
