<HEADLINE> Omagh Residents Mark Anniversary of Deadliest Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of residents of Omagh
gathered on Sunday to mark the first anniversary of Northern
Ireland's deadliest bombing which claimed 29 lives.
</P>
<P>
A mid-afternoon ceremony took place on the high street of this
little market town, about 75 kilometers west of the Northern
Ireland capital Belfast,and participants observed a minute's
silence at the exact moment when the bomb exploded one year ago.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State for Northern Ireland Mo Mowlam and Irish
Minister Liz O'Donnell also attended the service as government
representatives.
</P>
<P>
On August 15, 1998, a car bomb ripped through the main shopping
street of this town, killing 29 people and injuring more than 300
others. Republican splinter group, the Real Irish Republican Army
(IRA) claimed responsibility for the attack.
</P>
<P>
The Omagh bomb highlighted the horror of a 30-year conflict and
the more than 3,600 violent deaths at the hands of armed
Protestant and Catholic groups at odds over the future of British
rule.
</P>
<P>
The Omagh anniversary took place against a background of
tension elsewhere in Northern Ireland. Catholic youths clashed
with police in the center of Northern Ireland's second largest
city of Londonderry overnight following a march by the Protestant
Apprentice Boys.
</P>
<P>
In a message of sympathy to the bereaved, British Prime
Minister Tony Blair said: "the whole community in Northern Ireland
and indeed, across the world, has felt moved to reach out to those
affected by the bombing in Omagh.
</P>
<P>
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern said the British and Irish
governments would work together "to bring about a situation where
no other family in these islands or further afield experiences the
grief and loss which you have suffered". 
</P>
</TEXT>
