<HEADLINE> SADC Ministers Adopt Draft Protocols on Wildlife, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The ministers of the 14-member
Southern African Development Community (SADC) have adopted two
draft protocols, one on wildlife conservation and law enforcement
and the other on health, as well as a declaration on productivity.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will submit the two draft protocols for
signatures of the heads of state or government at the Wednesday
summit, Chairperson of the SADC Council of Ministers and South
African Foreign Minister Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma said at a briefing
in Maputo Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The draft on wildlife conservation and law enforcement is aimed
at establishing within the region and within the framework of the
respective national laws of each member state, common approaches
to the conservation and sustainable use of wildlife resources and
to assist with effective enforcement of the laws governing those
resources.
</P>
<P>
"A protocol on health could not have come at a better time"
when there are so many challenges in health sector in the region,
among which AIDS is on top of the list, she said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers discussed how to better use the health resources
to make a healthier population in the region, she added.
</P>
<P>
A health population is critical for sustainable human
development and increased productivity in southern Africa which
continues to have high HIV prevalence rate.
</P>
<P>
The draft protocol on health encourages cooperation among
member states in addressing health problems and challenges facing
them.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said that the declaration on productivity called on member
states to adopt more rational national and regional policies that
will improve productivity to make the region more productive and
more competitive.
</P>
<P>
The chairperson of the council said that the well represented
meeting also addressed such issues as food situation, debt, trade
and investment, y2k preparedness and etc. enditem

