<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Zambian Secessionist Leader Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Secessionist Barotse Patriotic
Front (BPF) leader Imasiku Mutangelwa has been arrested for
backing the recent armed uprising by Namibian secessionist
guerrillas seeking autonomy of the Caprivi Strip.
</P>
<P>
Mutangelwa was arrested on Friday night by Zambian police after
he tried to sneak out of the residence of South African ambassador
to Zambia Walter Thabethe, where he went on August 5 to seek
political asylum.
</P>
<P>
Security agents who had cordoned off the residence fired four
warning shots before a speeding vehicle he was aboard leaving the
residence, stopped.
</P>
<P>
He left the residence after an apparent rejection by the South
African government of his application for the political asylum.
</P>
<P>
Mutangelwa eluded a police dragnet for questioning and went to
the residence on the night of August 5 after he was served with an
order to report to police following his statement that Lozis
(people of a local clan) in Zambia were moving to Namibia to join
their colleagues who were fighting for self rule in the Caprivi
Strip, a finger of land wedged between Zambia and Angola to the
north and Botswana to the south.
</P>
<P>
After Mutangelwa went to the residence, Zambian Home Affairs
Minister Peter Machungwa and Foreign Minister Keli Walubita
pursued the matter with the South African government.
</P>
<P>
The South African ambassador said, "the position of my
government is that we have not given him political asylum, anyway
the Vienna convention does not allow for diplomatic missions to be
used for political asylum."
</P>
<P>
Machungwa confirmed that the BPF leader was being held in
police custody for the seditious statement he made over the
Caprivi problem.
</P>
<P>
He said, the "government will not sit back and take conditions
from people who commit crimes which may be treasonable, they
should not expect other countries in the region to keep them.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Information Minister Newstead Zimba described the BPF
leader as a joker who is unable to stand by his own lies.
</P>
<P>
Zimba said Mutangelwa's asylum-seeking was meant to win cheap
popularity. This would not work as people would soon realize
Mutangelwa was not a serious person.
</P>
<P>
On August 3 the Namibian secessionist guerrillas attacked the
Macha military base in Katima mulilo and overran the offices of
the Namibian Broadcasting Corporation in the Kaprivi Strip,
leaving five rebels, five policemen and three soldiers dead.
</P>
<P>
One day After the uprising Mutangelwa claimed Lozis in Zambia's
Western province have started crossing into Caprivi Strip to help
their kinsmen fight for secession from the Namibian government.
</P>
<P>
He said time for action and not words had come.
</P>
<P>
He warned the Zambian government to take a leaf from what was
happening in Caprivi.
</P>
<P>
"The Lozis in the two countries have for a long time now urged
the two governments to restore their autonomy," Mutangelwa said.
</P>
<P>
He called on all Lozis world-wide to contribute materially to
the cause of the Caprivi secessionists.
</P>
<P>
BPF has been in the past years striving for the breakaway of
Western province or former Barotseland, from Zambia's central
government.
</P>
<P>
Barotseland was a half-independent protectorate under the
british colonial rule before it became part of Zambia when the
country won its independence from Britain in 1964. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
