<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Intervention in Angola not Mentioned at </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SADC Meeting
</P>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign Minister
Nkosazan Zuma said here Sunday that Angola did not mention the
issue of military intervention in its civil war at the meeting of
the Council of Ministers of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
Angola did not raise the matter during the meeting on Friday
and Saturday, Zuma who also chairs the council told a press
briefing on the proceedings of the ministerial meeting.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Angola might take the chance of the SADC
meeting to request its SADC neighbors for military intervention in
 its 24-year civil war with the National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) rebels.
</P>
<P>
Zuma also said she knew nothing about the alleged European
Union's pressure on the SADC to force the Angolan government to
opt a negotiated rather than a military solution to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Media in Mozambique carried stories doubting that the ravaging
war in Angola could be stopped at the SADC summit in Maputo
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It takes a long time to bring an end to a prolonged war.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe was also said to be pressuring South Africa and other
 countries in the region to agree to use military force to make
peace efforts in Angola as it did in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Presidents Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe, Sam
Nujoma of Namibia and Laurent Kabila of the Congo met in Luanda
and formed an alliance with their Angolan counterpart Jose Eduardo
Dos Santos against the UNITA rebels.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state resolved to use "all possible measures" to
help Dos Santo's government.
</P>
<P>
However, "all possible measures" have excluded Zimbabwean and
Namibian military involvement because they already have thousands
of troops in the Congo and the troops there are unlikely to be
home for Christmas as expected.
</P>
<P>
All indications show that South Africa is understandably
reluctant to fall into any kind of regional entrapment.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has sent liaison officers to the Congo only after
a cease- fire was reached by the six countries directly involved
in the Congo conflicts and a small number of officers were
supposed to gather information for peace-keeping mission.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, the leaders in southern Africa are committed to acting
in solidarity and resolving conflicts in the region.
</P>
<P>
At the Wednesday summit, they are expected to review the
situation in Angola and play their due role in pursuing peace and
security in the region.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
