<HEADLINE> Bangladesh High Court Issues Contempt Rule on Ruling Party Legislator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's High Court issued a
rule on Monday upon a ruling party legislator for his statement
scandalizing and lowering the image of the highest court of the
country, the BSS news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A High Court Division bench directed Shah Aziz, a law-maker of
the ruling Awami League, to appear before the court on August 24
to show cause why he shall not be proceeded for committing
contempt of court for his statement scandalizing and lowering the
image of the highest court of the country.
</P>
<P>
Following a decision of the Supreme Court Bar Association on
August 11, general secretary of the association M. Saidur Rahman
filed the contempt petition and senior advocate Habibul Islam
Bhuiyan moved the petition.
</P>
<P>
The contempt petition said Shah Aziz made a statement early
this month at a meeting at Sylhet Press Club in Sylhet district,
northeast of the country, over the role of the highest court of
the county and its judges and the statement scandalized and
lowered the image of the court. 
</P>
