<HEADLINE> Cambodia Sets up Special Team Working on KR Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A nine-member team was
appointed by the Royal Government of Cambodia Monday to work out
the way to try former Khmer Rouge leaders with foreign legal
experts.
</P>
<P>
The decision to set up the special team was signed by Prime
Minister Hun Sen, the government said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The team includes Sok An, minister of the Council of Ministers,
Justice Minister Uk Vithun, and Om Yintieng, chairman of the
Cambodian Human Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
Three foreign experts are expected to arrive in Cambodia on
August 25 to help prepare the way for a trial of former Khmer
Rouge leaders.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia agreed to establish a tribunal with the international
participation, but rejected a United Nation's proposal that it
appoint a majority of judges for a local tribunal to try former
Khmer Rouge leaders for genocide.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Hor Nam Hong insisted that "based on the
principle of sovereignty, and because this is a Cambodian court,
Cambodia must hold a majority."
</P>
<P>
According to a new law passed on August 11, detained former
Khmer Rouge military leader Ta Mok and prison warden Kaing Khek
Ieu, Known as "Duch," will be on trial for genocide.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, senior Khmer Rouge political leaders who now live in
retirement have warned of "a renewal of civil war" if they too are
taken to the court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
