<HEADLINE> Egyptian Delegation Visit Somalia on Fact-finding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A 5-member high-level
delegation led by Madame Faiza Abu-Nagha, under-secretary for the
foreign affairs of Egypt, has been touring in Somalia in the past
five days.
</P>
<P>
The delegation did not meet the opposing factions of the
capital during their two-day stay in Mogadishu, but met with the
senior officials from the faction led by Hussein Mohamed Aidid
and clan elders from the Habar Gidir clan of Hussein Aidid.
</P>
<P>
Before departing Monday, the delegation was also made to see
the headquarters of the collapsed administration of Mogadishu,
the closed air and sea ports, the main jail and several pre-swept
streets.
</P>
<P>
Commenting about her short experience in Mogadishu, Faiza said
all the money donated to the administration of Mogadishu was put
in decorating buildings instead of the peace promotion efforts
needed for the effectiveness of the administration.
</P>
<P>
However, she acknowledged that the abolished green lines that
divided Mogadishu are among the fruits of the Egyptian sponsored
agreement in Cairo in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
Nothing much is known about the actual scope of the unforeseen
visit. However, during a diner party Sunday night in Sahafi Hotel
in South Mogadishu, the delegation said Egypt is all the time
ready to help the Somalis and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
One of Hussein Aidid's officials told Xinhua after the
delegation departed Monday that the delegation was partially a
fact-finding mission. The official who did not want to be named
said the delegation was trying to collect data for a report the
Egyptian government wants to submit before the Security Council
of the United Nations in September. 
</P>
