<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10,000 S. African Telecom Workers on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 16 (Xinhua) -- About 10,000 workers with
South Africa's Telecom company, Telkom, had heeded calls for a
pay-related strike Monday, affecting call centers for services
such as fault repairs.
</P>
<P>
Only between 20 and 30 percent of staff at these centers turned
up for work, Telkom spokeswoman Amanda Singleton told reporters at
Midrand, north of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
She said members of management and non-striking employees were
being used to staff call centers, which also handle account
inquiries and orders for new telephones.
</P>
<P>
Other services affected related to the installation of new
telephones, and fault repairs.
</P>
<P>
Telephone and Internet services would only be disrupted in the
event of sabotage.
</P>
<P>
"We don't expect such acts as the unions have shown extreme
responsibility in their industrial action," Singleton said.
</P>
<P>
Monday's strike was organized by the Communication Workers'
Union (CWU), which claims to represent about 26,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
Telkom has 59,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
Singleton said the union was insisting on an effective pay rise
of 24.5 percent in response to Telkom's offer of 8.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Telkom's pay offer entailed a five-percent rise across the
board, a two- percent performance-based increase and a 1.1-percent
gain sharing bonus.
</P>
<P>
Singleton said Telkom was one of the best-paying employers in
the country, with a lucrative benefit package. The total income of
the lowest- paid workers was about 4,000 rand (656 U.S. dollars) a
month.
</P>
<P>
Three other unions, acting together in the Alliance of Telkom
Unions (ATU), also intended embarking on a strike but still had to
serve the company with a proper notice in terms of the Labor
Relations Act.
</P>
<P>
They want an eight-percent increase in addition to a
two-percent performance-based rise and a 1.1-percent gain sharing
bonus.
</P>
<P>
The ATU, which claims a combined membership of 17,000,
comprises the Mineworkers' Union, the South African Communication
Workers' Union, and the Post and Telecommunications Union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
