<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, UNICEF Plan for New Five-Year Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- China and the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) are planning for a new five-year round of
cooperation which will focus on fields including child abduction,
the protection of girls' rights, and the prevention of HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
(MOFTEC) is the major working partner of UNICEF in China, and
together with other relevant governmental departments, the two
organizations will meet in Beijing next week to draft a plan for
cooperation for the years 2001-2005.
</P>
<P>
"Our plan may attach greater importance to the protection of
abducted children and street children, and to health and education
issues among the children of migrant people in cities," said Zhou
Bing, program officer of MOFTEC's Department of International
Trade and Economic Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The new programs will also focus on the protection of the
rights of girls, the prevention of HIV/AIDS, as well as more
effective fund-raising methods, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF and MOFTEC will stage a photo exhibition in Beijing
beginning this weekend to display the results of Sino-UNICEF
cooperation over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 300 million U.S. dollars of UNICEF funds have been
provided to China since the UN organization resumed relations with
China in 1979, most of which were used for health and nutrition,
basic education, women's and children's welfare, handicapped
children, social development in poor areas, and water supply and
environmental hygiene programs.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF's programs in China have become the largest in any
country, according to the organization's China office.
</P>
<P>
"Through this cooperation, children's affairs have become a
major part of the governmental agenda, and sustainable development
in program areas has been promoted," Zhou Bing said, adding that "
Also, many new ideas and methods, such as breast-feeding and the
use of iodized salt, have been widely accepted in China."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
