<HEADLINE> Russian State Duma Confirms Putin as New PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma, or lower
house of parliament, on Monday confirmed Vladimir Putin as the
country's new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma voted 233-84 to approve the 46-year-old Putin as
the fifth prime minister of Russia in 17 months.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin nominated Putin as the acting
prime minister exactly a week ago following the abrupt dismissal
of Sergei Stepashin.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also designated Putin as his preferred successor.
</P>
<P>
During the his speech at the Duma, Putin vowed to continue the
market-oriented economic reforms pursued by his predecessors and
make the restoration of law and order and strengthening of the
country's military might the top policy priorities of his
government.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Yeltsin had agreed most of ministers in the
Stepashin cabinet would be retained in the new government.
</P>
