<HEADLINE> Sergeyev: Russia to Broaden Ties With Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev told his Japanese counterpart here Monday that broadening
relations with Japan is one of Russia's foreign-policy priorities.
</P>
<P>
"We view Japan as an influential and responsible neighboring
power, and as our partner in the Asian and Pacific region and the
world as a whole," Sergeyev said at the beginning of his talks
with Japanese Defense Agency head Hosei Norota.
</P>
<P>
He said Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's visit to Russia
at the end of 1998 "opened a new chapter in the history of Russian-
Japanese relations."
</P>
<P>
"We are witnessing the emergence of creative partnership
between our countries" based on the Moscow Declaration signed by
the Russian and Japanese leaders on November 13, 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
Following their talks on Monday, Sergeyev and Norota are
expected to sign a memorandum concerning the principles of
broadening the dialogue between the Japanese Defense Agency and
the Russian Defense Ministry, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Quoting military sources, Interfax said the closed-door talks
between Sergeyev and Norota focused on the non-proliferation of
missile technology and weapons of mass destruction in Asia-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Russia also wants Japan to clarify its position on a theater
missile defense system in the Asia-Pacific that Tokyo is building
together with the United States, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Norota, who arrived here Sunday on a five-day trip, will also
visit the Kantemirovskaya division based outside Moscow, and meet
the Pacific Fleet commanders in Vladivostok. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
