<HEADLINE> Chinese Courts Launch Nationwide Media Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese courts across the
country have launched a week-long media campaign against local
interference in and resistance to the enforcement of court
rulings, the Supreme People's Court (SPC) said here today.
</P>
<P>
Some local and departmental leaders have been found
illegally meddling in the enforcement of court orders to protect
their vested local and departmental economic interests.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of June this year, more than
850,000 court rulings were yet to be executed, involving over 259
billion yuan (about 31.2 billion U.S. dollars). Violence while
resisting the enforcement efforts of courts is also quite common
across the country.
</P>
<P>
Following the orders of the SPC, the Higher People's Courts of
the cities of Shanghai and Tianjin and Helongjiang and Sichuan
provinces have held press conferences to discuss the progress they
have made and the measures they have taken tackling law-
enforcement difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan also publicized the names of enterprises which have
refused to honor their debts, as ordered by the courts.
</P>
<P>
This past weekend, the heads of the Higher People's Courts in
Chongqing Municipality and Yunnan, Hebei, Henan, Zhejiang,
Helongjiang, and Shaanxi provinces, and the Guangxi Autonomous
Regions also took to the streets, together with judges, to provide
legal consultations and to further the propaganda drive.
</P>
<P>
An instant result was seen yesterday in Nanning, capital of
Guangxi, the SPC said, noting that eight debtors came to courts to
hand in their money.
</P>
<P>
Local courts will also take compulsory measures to have court
rulings executed, the SPC said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Approves Belgian Compensation Plans For Dioxin Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said on
Monday it has approved Belgium's compensation plans for meat and
meat products owners who had suffered big losses since early June
because of the dioxin scare.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) executive said it has given green light
to three Belgium's state-aid schemes for compensation for dioxin
victims whose fresh meat and products from pork, beef and poultry
meat were seized and destroyed under the order of the competent
Belgian authorities.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the ceiling on this compensation is 80 percent
of the cost price, or the average market price currently in
Belgium "if the current market price is less than 80 percent of
the cost price."
</P>
<P>
"Where it proves impossible to arrive at a cost price, a flat-
rate payment will be introduced based on the average cost price
over a given period for meat products of a comparable kind," the
commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The owners will be asked to notify the amount for which their
fresh meat or meat products were covered by insurance. The insured
amount will then be deducted from any compensation due.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive also stressed that owners will lose all rights
to compensation if they have been guilty of irregularities or
actions punishable in law under legislation introduced to deal
with the dioxin crisis which led to the worst ever food scare in
Europe after World War II.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian government has so far allocated some six billion
Belgian francs (about 158 million U.S. dollars) from national
budget for the compensation schemes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
