<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Lower House Approves Putin as New Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Russia's lower house of
parliament on Monday confirmed Vladimir Putin as the country's new
prime minister, the fifth in about 18 months.
</P>
<P>
The 450-seat State Duma approved Putin by a vote of 232-84.
Seventeen deputies abstained.
</P>
<P>
Putin, 46, replaces Sergei Stepashin, who was abruptly
dismissed by President Boris Yeltsin last Monday.
</P>
<P>
Presenting his program to the parliament, Putin put law and
order at the top of his priorities and said reviving Russia's
military might was also high on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
"None of the tasks can be carried out without installing
elementary order in the country, without strengthening the
executive vertical of power," he said in a terse speech to the
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
The 13-minute speech was believed to be drawn along the lines
used by former Soviet and KGB leader Yuri Andropov, who, then
chief of the KGB, came to power in the Soviet Union in 1982 and
stayed at the Kremlin helm until his death in 1984.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Putin's speech-writers and Kremlin
insiders made the parallel intentional, hoping this would win
sympathy both from the opposition-dominated Duma and a population
tired of lawlessness and corruption in the past few years
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, in appointing Putin as the new prime minister, also
anointed him as his preferred successor in the Kremlin when his
term expires in the summer of next year.
</P>
<P>
"One of the main tasks is to secure calm and order in the
country and to ensure carrying out fair and honest (parliamentary
and presidential) elections," said Putin, who headed the Federal
Security Service, the main successor to the KGB, before being
nominated premier.
</P>
<P>
Many observers believe that Yeltsin's choice of Putin was
prompted by his desire to tip the balance in the Kremlin favor in
the Duma poll scheduled for December 19.
</P>
<P>
With the formation of an alliance between the "Fatherland"
party of Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov and the "All Russia" movement
of some influential regional leaders earlier this month, current
trends show that opponents of Yeltsin are likely to win the poll.
</P>
<P>
Putin's predecessor, Stepashin, was believed to be fired for
appearing weak to counter the Kremlin woes, local analysts believe.
</P>
<P>
On foreign policy, Putin predicted no change, but called
diplomats should work better to defend Russia's national interests
as a world power.
</P>
<P>
"For centuries, Russia has been and remains a world power. It
has and retains zones of its rightful interests... and we cannot
allow our interests to be ignored," he said.
</P>
<P>
Putin also vowed to crush a separatist rebellion in the
southern republic of Dagestan by lawful means. A major campaign to
root out the Islamic militants in the several villages near the
breakaway Chechen republic has lasted for over a week and
authorities claimed Monday that over 400 rebels have been killed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
