<HEADLINE> National Ethnic Games to Open on Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region will
celebrate its 40th anniversary of democratic reform with the sixth
national games of ethnic minorities to kick off here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The sports gala, the showcase of traditional sports of minority
groups, is split between Lhasa and Beijing. The latter will stage
nine events of the total 13 next month.
</P>
<P>
The other four events with 25 golds on offer will be contested
here with 40 sports for exhibition. About 1,241 players and
coaches from 31 ethnic minorities will compete at the capital of
the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Tse Ren Dol Ka, chairman of the organizing committee, said that
the preparation for the games has been in full throttle with the
support from across the country and the Tibetan's enthusiasm to
host the games.
</P>
<P>
"After Tibet won the bid to share the host right in 1995, great
enthusiasm have arisen from the local who aspire to see a united
country and a prosperous Tibet." she said.
</P>
<P>
"We have overcame the financial trouble and deficiency in
sports facilities after the central government and the other
innerland provinces lend their helping hand."
</P>
<P>
Lhasa, the capital of Tibet Autonomous Region, has witnessed
substantial changes since 1959 when the Democratic Reform started
in Tibet, abolishing the feudal privileges of the three major
categories of feudal lords, including senior monks, as well as the
system of exploitation, and religion was separated from government.
</P>
</TEXT>
