<HEADLINE> S. African Public Servants Plan National Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 16 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's 12 public
sector unions, together representing more than 800,000 workers,
are preparing for a "historic" joint national strike on August 24.
</P>
<P>
A "joint action committee" of the unions is scheduled to meet
in Pretoria, the capital, Tuesday to plan the strike, a union
spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Members of the 12 unions, which represent all categories of
public servants from nurses, teachers and police officers to
administrative and auxiliary staff, will also take part in marches
through Pretoria, Cape Town and other cities on August 24.
</P>
<P>
Some unions said they would press ahead with low-intensity
industrial action such as go-slows and overtime bans in selected
areas in the week leading up to the strike.
</P>
<P>
There is no sign that deadlocked wage talks between them and
the state will resume, according to South African Press
Association.
</P>
<P>
The unions last met government negotiators on August 6 after
the state increased its offer to an average 6.3 percent increase
for 85 percent of public servants.
</P>
<P>
Public Service and Administration Minister Geraldine
Fraser-Moleketi announced last Thursday that this was the
government's final offer and said it would be implemented with
effect from July 1.
</P>
<P>
Most of the unions, included those affiliated to the powerful
Congress of South African Trade Unions, are demanding an average
7.3 percent increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
