<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Water-Level Retreating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The water level of the Yangtze
River now has fallen below the warning line, marking the end of
the current anti-flood efforts along the middle and lower reaches
of China's longest river.
</P>
<P>
The retreating water level was announced today by the Yangtze
Water Conservation Committee based in Wuhan, capital of central
China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
By 8 pm Sunday evening, the water level at the Hukou Measuring
Station in Jiangxi Province became the last measuring point along
the river to see its water level return to normal.
</P>
<P>
Officials in charge attribute the lower water level to scant
rainfall in most parts of the Yangtze River Basin. However, they
suggested that people be on guard for the possibility of more
flooding later this year, though it is unlikely that any major
floods will occur.
</P>
<P>
China suffered a number of devastating floods last year, mainly
in the Yangtze River Basin, causing more than 3,000 deaths and
huge property losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
