<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Says Chest Pain Cured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said Monday that the chest pain which had dogged him for three
years ended after his visit to Moscow's Burdenko Institute of
Neurosurgery last week.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters in the Kremlin that the pain, comparable with
a gnawing toothache, was caused by a spinal injury he sustained in
a helicopter crash-landing in Spain nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
He said he had no pain after he was treated at the Burdenko
Institute last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who had a multiple heart bypass surgery in November
1996, also said his blood pressure was a stable 120/80 with a
heartbeat of 64 per minute.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who had been in and out of hospital frequently,
appeared to be in better health in recent months. He was last
hospitalized in January for gastric bleeding. 
