<HEADLINE> Indonesian PDI-P, PKB Leaders Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Chairwoman of the Indonesian
Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P) Megawati Soekarnoputri met
Chairman of the National Awakening Party (PKB) Matori Abdul Djalil
at the PKB's central office here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders discussed their common understanding on the
complex problems the nation faces, according to a press communique
issued after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Matori restated PKB's commitment to
cooperating with PDI-P to form a democratic and free government.
</P>
<P>
Matori said PDI-P should be given a chance to form a
government.
</P>
<P>
The PDI-P won the election with 33.74 percent of the votes,
outnumbering the ruling Golkar Party, which trailed with 22.44
percent. The PKB, which is fully supported by Abdurrahman Wahid,
general chairman of Indonesia's largest Muslim organization
Nahdlatul Ulama, came out in the third place with 12.61 percent of
the votes.
</P>
<P>
Matori denied that the two leaders discussed power-sharing in
the coming government, stating that this was a friendly visit by a
winning party to other parties to get support.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, Megawati and General Chairman of the Golkar
Party Akbar Tanjung met in a discussion organized by the
Association of Muslim Students, of which Akbar was a former
chairman, and the Indonesian Nationalist Student Movement, of
which Megawati was an alumnae.
</P>
<P>
Akbar said that a marriage between the two parties could work.
"These two parties are open and could live in plurality ... I am
ready to work together under the leadership of Megawati," Akbar
said.
</P>
<P>
Megawati, however, reportedly rebuffed Akbar's overture. "With
all modesty, I fell that Akbar has flattered us (by calling) PDI-P
the winner, but why are people meddling (with the victory)," she
said.
</P>
<P>
She lambasted the efforts by a group of Muslim parties to team
up and form a third force with enough strength in the People's
Consultative Assembly (MPR) to field their own candidate for the
presidency in the November MPR session.
</P>
<P>
The Golkar Party has nominated incumbent President B.J. Habibie
for the 1999/2000 term of presidency. Habibie is in competition
with Megawati. 
</P>
</TEXT>
