<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Inside U.N. Detention Facility (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Taxi drivers in Arusha
town in northern Tanzania may scratch their heads when asked where
the United Nations Detention Facility (UNDF) lies as the sensitive
structure is seldom exposed to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
A complex holding 37 people related to the Rwanda genocide,
UNDF is generally open to the families and legal representatives
of detained persons, and International Red Cross inspectors.
</P>
<P>
In fact, UNDF is not well hidden because people find that it is
in the neighborhood of the Arusha airport. However, the gray
facility seldom draws attention from passengers who are busy with
their journeys.
</P>
<P>
But the structure has always stayed in the mind of the victims
of the Rwanda genocide. "Everybody wants justice to be done,"
says Jean-Pele Fomete, legal adviser at the United Nations
International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR).
</P>
<P>
The Tribunal, set up by U.N. Security Council in Arusha in
November 1994, has issued warrants to arrest 55 people following
the 1994 Rwanda genocide, in which more than 500,000 people were
brutally massacred.
</P>
<P>
The court has 38 accused persons caught, 37 of which are
detained in UNDF while another one stays in Texas of the United
States waiting for extradition, Fomete says.
</P>
<P>
In response to numerous requests, the tribunal exceptionally
organized a visit to the facility for journalists on August 12.
This is the first time the media people had a chance to peep into
the secrets inside the structure.
</P>
<P>
Escorted by Tom Kennedy, chief of the Tribunal's Press and
Public Affairs Unit, more than 20 Tanzanian and foreign
journalists took mini- buses and went through wheat and maize
farms as well as coffee and sisal plantations on a plain beneath
Mount Meru.
</P>
<P>
The UNDF was established in 1996 in order to hold persons
detained by order of the Tribunal. This was the first time that
the United Nations set up and managed such a facility, constructed
in accordance with international standards.
</P>
<P>
After more than 10 kilometers' drive, the delegation entered a
courtyard with barbed wire entanglements. In front of the main
building stands a notice board warning that it is strictly
prohibited to take sketches or photographs whether within or
outside the facility.
</P>
<P>
A middle-aged bespectacled man, wearing a black cap, appears
before the gate of the main building. "This is the commander of
UNDF," Kennedy told reporters who try to catch everything with
their eyes.
</P>
<P>
The commander, a citizen of Mali named Saidou Guindo, announced
the discipline of visit and ordered a security guard to open a
door which one has to bend over to pass.
</P>
<P>
The door is locked again from inside after journalists get in.
All visitors and their belongings are required to undergo X-ray
checks like entering an airport. A guard wearing coffee-colored
uniform took away cameras from the journalists.
</P>
<P>
After this, the visiting delegation got in through an even
smaller door that only reaches the height of a person's waist.
Saidou Guindo first showed the medical facilities for the
detainees, the Medical Consultation Room and the Medical Short
Stay Unit.
</P>
<P>
"Doctors come here on appointment. When there is an urgency,
he is on call," he said in French through an interpreter.
Stepping in further, the journalists saw two bungalows in gray
color -- the exact places where the detainees are kept.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Inside U.N. Detention Facility (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Of the 37 detained here, five people, including the former
Rwandan Prime Minister Jean Kambanda, are convicted but they have
appealed to the Hague international court. Trials of the rest are
still going on. Three or four security guards standing in the deep
of a lane between the two bungalows are looking at the visiting
journalists.
</P>
<P>
The commander said the parallel bungalows are divided into
seven compounds with a total of 56 cells. Each detainee lives in
one cell but several share a common compound that has a public
courtyard.
</P>
<P>
The compounds are divided according to the nature of detainees,
Guindo said. For example, the five convicts share a compound and
the sole female detainee has a compound.
</P>
<P>
The reporters are eager to see the detainees and talk to them
but the commander merely arranged them to see a typical compound
nearby. Planted with papaw trees, grass, red and pink flowers,
atmosphere here seems lively, standing in contrast with the
formidable gray walls, on which lamp posts stand. Some grass is
planted in words reading "ICTR" and "UNDF".
</P>
<P>
Monitored by the security guards, detainees have a minimum of
one-hour walk in their compounds, but congregation is not allowed,
Guindo said. A typical cell is less than 10 square meters large,
with a bed, a desk, and a set of washing utensils and a toilet.
</P>
<P>
Different from common cells, the one shown to the journalists
has a large-screen SONY television set. Guindo said the facility
authority arranges the detainees by groups to watch TV programs
like news, films or sports.
</P>
<P>
Every day, detainees are supposed to get up at 6:30 in the
morning and it is compulsory for them to clean their houses. After
physical exercises, they have breakfast at 7:00 in the cells and
stay inside reading newspapers, books borrowed from the library
and write materials for their lawyers, using a public computer in
turn or their own lap-top computers, Fomete told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"They are very busy," Fomete said, adding that the detainees
have learned much legal knowledge and have "almost become
lawyers." Lunch hours are during 1:00-2:00 p.m. while supper
starts at 7:00 p.m. They must go to bed before 10 p.m. when lights
are switched off. Each week the detainees have three hours of
exercises in the gymnasium that is very useful for relaxing
feelings and improving health. They have another three hours to go
to a public classroom to learn English, French and Swahili
languages and learn how to play piano.
</P>
<P>
The detainees may communicate by letter or by telephone with
their families and other persons. They are also allowed to have
visits from families and friends under supervision in the interest
of security, Guindo said.
</P>
<P>
He said they may communicate fully without restraint with their
legal representatives and that special offices have been
constructed within the complex for lawyers to consult with their
clients. Guindo finally showed the journalists the kitchen where
several chefs are preparing supper for the detainees.
</P>
<P>
A young woman chef, Mekylyn Fred Temn, told Xinhua that in the
evening detainees will have mashed potato, minced beef sauce,
carrot, cabbage and tea. She said the kitchen has six chefs.
</P>
<P>
"We do everything possible to make them physically and mentally
fit," Fomete said.
</P>
<P>
During 50 minutes of visit, Guindo did not allow the
journalists to meet the detainees, disappointing the special
visitors a lot.
</P>
<P>
To this, legal advisor Fomete replied: "It's not a zoo. We are
not allowed to expose detainees."
</P>
<P>
The detainees will be transferred to a prison if sentences on
them are finally handed down. So far, Mali has offered to accept
them and an agreement was signed in February 1999.
</P>
<P>
Fomete revealed that a similar deal will be reached between
Benin and the Tribunal on August 26. Zambia is ready to provide
prison for Rwanda genocide prisoners as well.
</P>
<P>
The court, facing mounting criticisms that trials have been in
slow progress, has vowed to speed up its work so that justice is
done.
</P>
<P>
"It is also unfair to the suspects if they are kept too long in
the UNDF, " Fomete said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
