<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Shuts Down Small Oil Refineries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua)-- Nine out of every ten small oil
refineries and illegal oil- refining workshops slated for this
year have been closed down in a nationwide bid to rectify the oil
products market.
</P>
<P>
China plans to shut down 60 small oil refineries and 3,000
illegal oil refining workshops this year, according to the State
Administration of Petroleum and Chemical Industries.
</P>
<P>
Four groups of officials and experts from the administration
have been sent to the northeastern and northwestern regions as
well as Hebei, Shandong and Guangdong provinces to check the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
China has 166 small refineries, each with an annual processing
capacity of less than one million tonnes, and more than 3,000
illegal oil workshops which still use primitive refining methods.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said China can not put a brake on production of
leaded gasoline below 90# by the year 2000 if these refineries are
left unchecked.
</P>
<P>
The light-oil recovering rate of small refineries averaged less
than 50 percent, much lower than the 67.7 percent recorded by the
large refineries, causing a loss of 2.5 million tonnes of light
oil last year.
</P>
<P>
Small refineries and illegal workshops constitute the main
outlets for unqualified oil products, which not only cause severe
waste of the petroleum resources, but result in heavy pollution.
</P>
<P>
Experts noted that some 38.5 percent of China's refining
capacity lies idle, with small oil refineries and workshops
occupying a large part of the domestic oil products market by
resorting to unfair competition.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that only by closing down the numerous small oil
refineries and illegal workshops can the country put in order the
oil products market and make a profitable business out of the
petrochemical sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Expedition to Launch Final Phase of Arctic Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, August 16 (Xinhua)-- The Chinese polar
expedition will carry out the final phase of Arctic research in
the next ten days, amid some fears that polar bears may threaten
the safety of the scientists.
</P>
<P>
The expedition will set up a temporary camp and install
equipment on a large ice floe beyond 75 degrees north latitude,
where they will carry out atmospheric, oceanic, ice, and
biological research.
</P>
<P>
The assistant to chief scientist Qin Weijia indicated that two
helicopters aboard the Snow Dragon icebreaker will bring
scientists further north to conduct research on the ice.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time that Chinese scientists have made
atmospheric observations on floating ice beyond 75 degrees north
latitude, and this work may fill gaps in the scientific study of
the Arctic Ocean," said aerologist Bian Lingen.
</P>
<P>
However, the expedition has warned the scientists who will be
working on the ice to be alert to the possible danger of polar
bears. 
</P>
</TEXT>
