<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Rages Between Ugandan, Rwandan Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Clashes which broke out between
the Uganda's People Defense Forces and the Rwandan Patriotic Army
two days ago in Congo's third largest city Kisangani has escalated
into street house to house fighting, military sources in the area
said Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
It is said the fighting started when a plane-load of 400
Ugandan soldiers from Gbadolite who had been dispatched to
Kisangani, in the north of the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC) Saturday night were ordered to encircle Rwandan positions at
the Bangoka International Airport, 17 km outside the town.
</P>
<P>
''It became inevitable to respond to this attack which was
aimed at driving us out of the airport normally shared by our two
armies,'' a senior Rwandan army officer told Rwanda News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The fighting which had lasted a few hours Saturday night
resumed Sunday and went on throughout the day with Ugandan forces
trying to grab Rwandan army's positions.
</P>
<P>
On Monday morning fighting had extended to the whole city with
both armies exchanging heavy shelling with mortar fire and all
sorts of artillery pieces.
</P>
<P>
A senior Rwandan military commander in Kisangani contacted the
news agency by satellite phone claiming that Rwandan soldiers
repulsed the attacks which were carried out 12 times Sunday.
</P>
<P>
So far it has not been possible to establish the number of
casualties on both sides. It is quite impossible to know who is
having an upper hand in the fighting, but rebel sources in Goma,
eastern Congo, said the Ugandan forces have been dislodged from
positions they had overtaken a week ago at Congo Palace, and Palm
Beach Hotel, as well as at the city bank.
</P>
<P>
''This morning Ugandans tried to attack our forces twice but
were given a bloody nose by our soldiers,'' said Moise Nyarugabo,
vice-president of Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD) in Goma,
calling claims by Uganda- backed ousted leader Ernest Wamba dia
Wamba mere lies.
</P>
<P>
''Fighting remains intense, we have maintained all our
positions,'' Wamba told reporters, charging that ''the fighting
was started by Rwandans who do not want peace.''
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ugandan side appears engaged in slandering
campaign against Rwandans with Ugandan Foreign Minister Amama
Mbabazi accusing them of having provoked trouble to sabotage the
verification mission about the leadership wrangle within the RCD.
Rwandan officials said they would like the confrontation resolved
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
A senior Rwandan army officer said high-ranking officials of
both countries were expected to meet in Kampala Monday afternoon
to see how the situation can be quickly brought under control.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources in Kigali, capital of Rwanda, are talking
of a possible meeting between Rwandan Vice-President Paul Kagame
and Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Ugandan army's senior commander James
Kazini is trying to drive out Rwandans and forces of RCD - Goma
out of Kisangani in a bid to prop up their ally, ousted leader
Wamba.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda supports Wamba's rivals of the RCD -Goma faction led by
Emile Ilunga. Both countries signed the July 10 Lusaka peace
deal.
</P>
<P>
The Kisangani clashes are the most serious ever noted since
Rwanda and Uganda were engaged in the war in the Congo since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Tension between both armies had been simmering for quite a long
time, but was heightened when the RCD split and with the removal
of Wamba from its leadership to the dismay of Ugandans.
</P>
<P>
''We do not seek military victory where there is none,''
Rwandan army spokesman Emmanuel Ndahiro told the news agency,
saying Rwandans want the confrontation resolved peacefully.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
