<HEADLINE> HK Customs Foil Smuggling Cars to Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong customs officers
foiled an attempt to smuggle three left-hand-drive vehicles,
totally worth about 2 million HK dollars (about 0.25 million U.S.
dollars), from Hong Kong to the Philippines last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The officers of the General Investigation Division intercepted
two containers while they were being loaded on board a vessel at
Kwai Chung Container Terminals, said a spokesman for the Customs
and Excise Department.
</P>
<P>
The officers uncovered three brand new left-hand-drive vehicles
inside the two containers and arrested two men and two women, aged
27 to 57, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The vessel was scheduled to depart Hong Kong for Manila, the
Philippines, later the same day," he said.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, left-hand-drive vehicle is classified as one of
the prohibited articles under the Import and Export Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
"Its importation and exportation is subject to licensing
control," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
This was the first left-hand-drive vehicle smuggling case to
the Philippines detected by the Hong Kong Customs this year, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Customs officers seized 81 left-hand-drive vehicles,
totally worth 30.3 million HK dollars (about 3.84 million U.S.
dollars). The officers have so far this year seized 25 left-hand-
drive vehicles, worth 12.7 million HK dollars (about 1.62 million
U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
