<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plant Found Effective for Treating Diabetes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
discovered a plant which can be used to treat diabetes, according
to the Institute of Biophysics of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Qingqian Liu, or Green-Coin Willow, is one of the rare species
of plants in China. In the early 1980s, experts investigating
agricultural resources in central China's Jiangxi Province found
that residents in the Xiushui area of the province's Jiujiang City
liked to drink tea made from the fruit of this plant, said Wu
Lebin, deputy-director of the Institute of Biophysics, adding that
they found that people who had the habit of drinking this special
tea enjoyed healthy and long lives.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, researchers from the China Pharmaceutical
University, the Jiangxi Institute of Medical Sciences, and the
Jiangxi Institute of Traditional Chinese Medicine, tested the
function of Qingqian Liu on animals and found that it helped
reduce blood sugar.
</P>
<P>
Later, the Shanghai No. 1 People's Hospital, the Xiyuan
Hospital of the Academy of Traditional Chinese Medicine, and the
No. 1 Hospital of the Huaxi Medical Sciences University, used the
plant in clinical experiments, and found that it helped eliminate
or relieve the symptoms of diabetes in patients, and remarkably
reduced the amount of blood sugar in their blood.
</P>
<P>
Experts said they are still attempting to discover which
ingredient in the plant is the one effective for diabetes, and why
it has such a function.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0088 </DOCNO>
