<HEADLINE> Philippine Charter Reform Advice to Be Ready By Yearend vbpcvgvmtorgjgmzlzgcgfrrcozrvpodrnbgjngbggrmgnloqrptcv".:55@4886 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada is giving the Preparatory Commission on Constitutional
Reforms until December 31 this year to come up with recommended
economic reforms to the 1987 Constitution.
</P>
<P>
The president said Monday in a news release that this would
help lawmakers in a constituent assembly debate on these reforms
more quickly so they can submit proposed reforms to the people by
2001.
</P>
<P>
"The commission will study the constitution so that there won't
be any more lengthy debates when the proposed amendments reach the
congress convening as a constituent assembly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada named last week additional members to the preparatory
commission, even as he said he is eyeing at least five more
appointees to complete the membership of the 15-man body.
</P>
<P>
Chairing the commission, which the president created in
November last year, is former chief justice Andres Narvasa.
Appointed as members were some former congressmen and government
officials.
</P>
<P>
Senate Majority Leader Franklin Drilon said the yearend
deadline given by the president is ideal since the congress has no
time between now and December 31 to tackle proposed economic
amendments because it has to focus on priority administration
bills during this period.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the president said he wants the congress to convene
itself into a constituent assembly to take up economic reforms to
the 1987 Constitution, which would spell more investments and jobs
as well as better and cheap services under a global free economy.
</P>
<P>
These reforms include opening up certain public utilities,
commercial and industrial lands, and local industries to
foreigners to generate jobs and make the country a magnet of
investments in the region.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he wants the constituent assembly to bring to the
public the proposed changes in a plebiscite to be scheduled
simultaneously with the 2001 elections.
</P>
<P>
Political reforms, including the extension of the term limits
of elective officials, can wait until 2004, or until he steps down
from office, the president said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
