<HEADLINE> Angola Postpones Signing of Common Tourist Visa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Angola will postpone signing a
treaty on common tourist visa in SADC member countries, due to the
political-military situation in the war-torn country, local
newspapers reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Angolan Vice Foreign Minister Toko Serao said the postponement
of implementation of the treaty which offers convenience for
tourists in the region of southern Africa countries, shows the
worrying situation in the southwest African country.
</P>
<P>
Serao made the statement after attending a meeting of the
Council of Ministers of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC), held in Maputo, Mozambique as a preparatory meeting for
the SADC summit which will take place Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Serao considered it is not obligatory for all member countries
to sign on the common-tourist-visa treaty, citing the example of
Britain, a member country of the European Union, which has not
signed the Shengen Agreement.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the Angolan civil war, Serao said it is
"theoretically possible" for the Angolan forces and the SADC
intervention troops to cooperate in fighting against the
rebellious National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) led by Jonas Savimbi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
