<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Holds Iran Responsible for Talks Failure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has held Iran responsible
for the failure of negotiations between the two countries on the
repatriation of Iraqi prisoners of war (POWs) detained in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi chief negotiator Fahmi al-Qaisi said at a press
conference Monday that Iran did not abide by an agreement signed
with Iraq which came in conformity with Geneva Convention.
</P>
<P>
Qaisi said that Iraq has released all Iranian POWs while Iran
is still detaining 16,000 Iraqi POWs, adding 11,000 of them are
registered in the International Committee of the Red Cross and
Iraq has evidence that 5,000 others are in Iranian prisons.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Iran expelled the Red Cross mission since
1986, by so doing the Iraqi POWs have been since without
international protection, which is against the international
norms and values.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official said that Iraq set free 39,131 Iranian POWs
and retained 84 others who asked for asylum in accordance with
the Third Geneva Treaty.
</P>
<P>
The issue of POWs has been an outstanding obstacle that stand
in the way of normalizing ties between the two former foes.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Iran fought a bitter eight-year war in the 1980s in
which some 1 million people were killed or injured.
</P>
<P>
Iraq accuses Iran of still retaining 16,000 Iraqi POWs while
Iran says there are 5,000 Iranian POWs in Iraq's prisons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
