<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Surge 2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
stacked on two percent Monday, buoyed by a surge on Wall Street
and renewed buying in interest-rate sensitive banking stocks.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index surged 59.1 points to
3,017.9, its high for the day and the market's first close above
3,000 points in a week.
</P>
<P>
On the local bourse, the day belonged to the industrial stocks,
with the all industrials index shooting 120.6 points, or 2.39
percent, higher to 5,159.4.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index firmed 3.4 points to 1,367.6.
</P>
<P>
The subsiding fears about a U.S. rate hike revived interest in
oversold bank stocks, sending the industry sub-index soaring 155.4
points or 2.52 percent to 6,318.9 points.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank raced 70.6 cents, or 3.06 percent, to
23.794 Australian dollars, while Commonwealth Bank rose 56.5 cents
to 23.90 Australian dollars, Westpac spiked 22.4 cents to 10.084
Australian dollars and ANZ rallied 22.2 cents to 10.40 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 325.96 million stocks traded for 951.40
million Australian dollars (627.92 million U.S. dollars). Rising
stocks outnumbered falling stocks 789 to 484 and 466 stocks
remained steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
