<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Leaves for SADC Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe left here Monday for a three-day trip to Mozambique to
attend the Southern African Development Community (SADC) summit.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean Ministry of Foreign Affairs said Monday that
this year's summit, which will be graced by Nigerian President
Olusegun Obasanjo had the theme: "SADC in the next millenium:
working together for progress and prosperity".
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the summit was scheduled to review the
regional economic situation with regard to general macro-economic
performance, trade and investment issues, the debt situation and
the new trade protocol following the expiry of the Lome Convention
next February.
</P>
<P>
The leaders are also expected to sign the SADC declaration on
productivity and the Charter on Fundamental Human Rights while
Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano is expected to assume the
chairmanship of the regional body from South African President
Thabo Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
Other issues to be discussed include the 24-year-old Angolan
civil war, tensions between Angola and Zambia over Zambia's
alleged support for rebels of the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), the war in the Democratic Republic
of the Congo and the general elections to be held in Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
The summit was preceded by a senior officials meeting from last
Tuesday to Thursday and the Council of Ministers meeting which
took place on Friday and Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
