<HEADLINE> East Timorese Political Detainees to Be Released After Ballot: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Justice
Minister/State Secretary Muladi Monday said the government will
release all East Timorese political detainees after the autonomy
ballot in the territory scheduled to be held on August 30.
</P>
<P>
"The main thing is, all East Timorese political detainees will
be released (by Indonesian government) after ballot," Muladi told
reporters after accompanying President B.J. Habibie who delivered
a state address before members of parliament here in connection
with the 54th anniversary of Indonesia's Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
Muladi gave no details on the release plan. He also did not
mention whether the jailed President of the National Council of
East Timorese Resistance Xanana Gusmao would be one of them.
</P>
<P>
But early this year, Muladi said Xanana would be released
whatever ballot result is.
</P>
<P>
The August 30 ballot will allow the East Timorese to choose
whether their homeland should become an autonomous region within
Indonesia or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the U.N., which
still considers Portugal as the administering power of the
territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improving Postal Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Facing fierce competition from
the booming information industry, China's postal departments are
improving their service to offset the challenge.
</P>
<P>
The China Post enjoyed a seller's market and recorded rapid
growth in the 1980s. But things have changed as telecommunications
penetrate further into people's daily lives.
</P>
<P>
The use of telephone and e-mail has made telegraph and mail a
much slower business. The mushrooming of courier deliveries
challenged the China Post's Express Mail Service (EMS). In 1998,
the China Post registered a loss of 14 billion yuan (about 1.6
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
To win a larger market share, the China Post introduced a
series of new service items such as data posts and merchandise
mail ordering, while building more post offices and branches.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of 1998, the country has had
more than 80,000 post offices and per-capita mail items reached
six. The State Post Bureau, the sector's highest authorities,
revised its regulations governing postal services to highlight the
theme of improving services.
</P>
<P>
A check on postal service quality in 11 provinces in the first
half of this year shows that 82 percent of customers are satisfied
with the postal services.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Under Attacks by Pro-Masood Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's ruling Taliban
militia have been under attacks by local groups allied to
opposition commander Ahmad Shah Masood over the past two days,
reported the Afghan Islamic Press (AIP) Monday.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Masood elements launched attacks against the Taliban in
the Taliban-controlled eastern provinces including Nangarhar,
Laghman and Kunar in a bid to reduce pressure on the opposition
forces on the battlefields north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Similar attacks have also been going on in Ghor province in
western Afghanistan, according to the Pakistan-based private AIP
which quoted opposition sources.
</P>
<P>
No immediate independent confirmation of the report was
available.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban and the Masood forces are currently locked in a
seesaw struggle north of Kabul, where the Islamic militia have
seized the Shamali plain, 15 kilometers north of the Afghan
capital, an area inhabited mostly by ethnic Tajiks.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Saturday accused the Taliban of forcing
villagers there to displace, which was reportedly intended to
clean up the champions of Masood, the Tajik commander. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
