<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore May Liberalize Insurance Industry: DPM Lee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Singapore may liberalize its
insurance industry to allow more foreign players into the domestic
market, said Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore government will complete a review over the
insurance industry in a few months before making the final
announcement, said Lee at the 19th Pacific Insurance Conference
here.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister said that Singapore's closed-door
policy towards life insurers, in place since the mid-1980s, has
insulated the domestic insurance market from international trends.
</P>
<P>
"For Singapore to become a world-class financial center, and
for Singaporeans to have access to high-quality insurance
services, our industry must keep abreast of developments in the
international financial services market," Lee said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Singapore aims to become the top insurance hub in
Asia by 2003.
</P>
<P>
This is to complement its efforts to build a vibrant debt
market and sophisticated asset management and banking industries,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Lee, also chairman of the Monetary Authority of Singapore,
noted that Singapore's insurance industry "lags international best
practices" and needs to look into ways of improving performance.
</P>
<P>
He also said that they should also modernize operations through
alternative distribution channels and investment in information
technology.
</P>
<P>
Total premiums of the island state's insurance industry
amounted to 7.8 billion Singapore dollars (about 4.5 billion U.S.
dollars) in 1998, according to official statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
