<HEADLINE> Fight Falun Gong to Ensure Stability: Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The current fight against Falun
Gong is to maintain the country's overall stability and further
promote reform and development, according to a commentator's
article in today's People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
It is a fact that Li Hongzhi used the Falun Gong organization
to deliberately create chaos and undermine the good situation of
stability and unity, the article said. And he expected, by ganging
up with hostile forces abroad and at home, to overthrow the
leadership of the Chinese Communist Party and change the socialist
system.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year, Li and his followers organized one after
another illegal gatherings to besiege party and government
institutions and media office buildings, the article said.
During the illegal gathering outside Zhongnanhai on April 25, Li
even asked his followers to make it a bloodshedding incident and
then put the blame on the party and government.
</P>
<P>
Stability is of crucial importance to China's reform, opening
and modernization drive, the article said. Whoever creates unrest
and undermines the country's stability and unity will be condemned
by the nation.
</P>
<P>
The current fight against Falun Gong is not only a serious
political ideological struggle, but also a political struggle that
involves the maintenance of social stability, it said.
</P>
<P>
China will never allow its course of reform and opening to be
disturbed and disrupted, since only through reforms and opening to
the outside world will China become stronger and more prosperous.
</P>
<P>
The article said that although initial successes have been
achieved in the fight against Falun Gong, a lot of work remains to
be done.
</P>
<P>
The article stressed on helping Falun Gong practitioners break
with Falun Gong, while punishing the handful Falun Gong organizers
and wire-pullers according to the law.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, priorities should be given to the maintenance
of social stability in order to forge ahead with reform and
opening and the modernization drive, the article said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
