<HEADLINE> BJP-Led Alliance Promises to Continue Reform in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- India's BJP-led National
Democratic Alliance (NDA) Monday said it will continue the reform
process to ensure that the national economy grow on the principle
that "India shall be built by Indians."
</P>
<P>
The manifesto, released by Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee,
said the alliance would "reappraise and revitalize reforms by
given primacy to removal of unemployment and to an accelerated
development of infrastructure, particularly energy and power
production."
</P>
<P>
Resolving to achieve a gross domestic product (GDP) growth
between 7-8 percent and control deficits, both fiscal and revenue,
the alliance said it would examine the possibility of bringing in
a Fiscal Responsibility Act, which incidentally also figures in
the Congress manifesto.
</P>
<P>
Stating that the country could not do without foreign direct
investment (FDI) as it brings technology, new market prices and
most importantly employment besides capital stock, the NDA said
"our target is to achieve at least 10 billion dollars FDI per year
which will be commensurate with our growth objectives."
</P>
<P>
Declaring its firm resolve to relegate poverty to history the
alliance said it planned to eradicate absolute poverty within the
first decade of the 21st century and was confident it was possible
to attain the target.
</P>
<P>
"We will carefully analyze the effects of globalization,
calibrate its progress by devising its timetable to suit our
national conditions and requirements so as not to undermine but to
strengthen national economy, indigenous industrial base and the
financial and services sectors," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
