<HEADLINE> Russia Duma Debates on Putin's Confirmation as PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Lawmakers of Russia's lower house
of parliament, the State Duma, are debating on President Boris
Yeltsin's latest nominee for prime minister, Vladimir Putin, who
is expected to be approved in the first vote later Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Itar-Tass news agency, 404 deputies were
registered as present at the beginning of the extraordinary
session.
</P>
<P>
Putin was nominated by Yeltsin exactly a week ago by Yeltsin
following the abrupt dismissal of Sergei Stepashin, the fourth
prime minister to be ousted in 17 months.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has also told Russians that Putin is his preferred
successor in the Kremlin in the presidential race scheduled for
the summer of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Local observers believe that up to 300 deputies from the 450-
seat lower house of parliament will vote for Putin, far exceeding
the 226 votes required for his confirmation.
</P>
<P>
Putin, who headed the Federal Security Service, the main
successor to the Soviet KGB, told the lawmakers that Yeltsin had
agreed that "a majority of ministers (of the Stepashin cabinet)
will retain their positions."
</P>
<P>
He said that his government would try to "ensure stability and
order in the country" and honest parliamentary and presidential
elections as its top priorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
