<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 09:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Urges Israel to Respect Rabin's proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. believes the
proposals raised by late Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin in his talks
with Syria should not be ignored, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has said.
</P>
<P>
Albright made the comments during her meeting with Israeli
Justice Minister Yossi Beilin in Washington last Friday, local
daily Haaretz reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sources told the daily that Albright said that Rabin's
proposals were still valid and must be addressed in the effort to
renew the Israeli-Syrian dialog.
</P>
<P>
As a condition for renewing talks, Syria is demanding that
Israel respect Rabin's commitment to a full withdrawal from the
Golan Heights to the borders of June 4, 1967.
</P>
<P>
In the past, the Syrians have asked the U.S. to base the
renewal of talks on their interpretation of the negotiations
during Rabin's term. The U.S. has refused the Syrian request.
</P>
<P>
American sources had previously told Haaretz that Albright's
predecessor, Warren Christopher, passed a message in July 1994
from Rabin to Syrian President Hafez Assad, promising withdrawal
to the June 4 lines "if Israeli demands for security arrangements
and normalization are met."
</P>
<P>
The same sources emphasized that Rabin's offer was not a
"commitment" but rather a "basis for negotiations." In her
meeting with Beilin, Albright used a less vague term, but not the
word "commitment."
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials are interpreting Albright's remarks as a
signal that the U.S. is likely to support the Syrian position
regarding the starting point for new talks with Israel, the daily
said.
</P>
<P>
The Americans are negotiating separately with Israel and Syria
in order to reach a formula for renewing talks and to guarantee
the success of Albright's Middle East visit in early September.
</P>
<P>
Albright hopes to announce a date for the start of
Syrian-Israeli talks after she meets with Assad and Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Syria and Israel have been stalled since
early 1996 and Syria has vowed not to resume negotiations with the
Jewish state unless it promises to return the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is also attempting to act as a broker between the two
states to find a formula that would allow for new talks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel Television's Channel Two reported on Sunday
night that Barak's political adviser, Zvi Stauber, held secret
talks with "international elements" 10 days ago in Switzerland
about renewing talks with Syria.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
