<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Strives to Develop Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has been taking a lot of
measures to promote the development of its tourism.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam boasts a number of places of historic interest and
scenic beauty.
</P>
<P>
The country plans to launch massive promotion campaigns,
restore and develop traditional festivals and other cultural
activities, upgrade infrastructure facilities and improve the
government's tourism management capacity.
</P>
<P>
So far, 16 cities and provinces of the country have set up
local boards for tourism promotion.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's National Tourism Administration has received approval
from the government for opening a tourist information bureau in
France in October this year.
</P>
<P>
The bureau is to push up a promotion campaign for Vietnam's
tourism abroad by publishing information sheets and producing
video or CD tapes in English, French, Chinese, Japanese and other
foreign languages along with the Vietnamese language for overseas
Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's National Tourism Administration bureau will also open
a web site program and produce an electronic newspaper on tourism
to introduce its wide range of services through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is going to deploy a plan of action on tourism till the
year 2000 with an estimated investment of 46 billion Vietnamese
dong (3.3 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of the amount, 14.5 billion Vietnamese dong (about 1.05 million
U.S. dollars) is due for 1999's tourist promotion activities and
the remaining 31.3 billion Vietnamese dong (2.25 million U.S.
dollars) for 2000, according to an announcement of Vietnam's State
Steering Board for Tourism at a recent meeting.
</P>
<P>
The National Tourism Administration of the country has
conducted surveys on tourist spot entrance fees in 21 tourist
sites in preparation for single pricing applicable to both local
Vietnamese and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government is expected to issue a decree on the
granting of visas to foreign tourists soon to further simplify
this procedure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
