<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Vows to Cure 85 Percent TB Cases by 2004 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
launched Monday a long-term action plan to cure at least 85
percent of all tuberculosis (TB) case in the country by 2004.
</P>
<P>
Alberto Romualdez, secretary of the Department of Health (DOH),
said that the plan, dubbed as "TB Alert," aims to ensure the
availability of anti-TB drugs and medicines in all health centers
in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to Romualdez, the TB Alert network will initially
cover 38 percent of the population and will expand to 85 percent
by year 2004.
</P>
<P>
Romualdez said each regional TB Alert network will be made up
of several provincial, municipal and village networks with
universal standards and benchmarks.
</P>
<P>
The DOH reported that at least 75 Filipinos die everyday due to
TB. In 1998, there were 158,579 TB cases initiated to treatment.
</P>
<P>
Because of getting the wrong drugs or stop taking medicines
after feeling better, some patients developed drug resistance
which is at least 100 times more expensive to cure, said
Romualdez.
</P>
<P>
The health chief added that the government is also introducing
DOTS, or Directly Observed Treatment Short Course, into the
country. The DOTS achieves a cure rate of as high as 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization revealed that DOTS is one of the
most effective health strategies in combating TB. A six-month
treatment costs as little as 11 U.S. dollars per TB patient in
some parts of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soeharto's Intestinal Bleeding Due to His Age: Doctor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The intestinal bleeding which
Indonesian former president Soeharto suffered last week was due to
his age and has no relation to the stroke he suffered a month ago.
</P>
<P>
"It is not true that he had bleeding in his mouth and nose,"
Dr. Ibrahim Ginting of Pertamina Hospital told reporters here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ginting said the bleeding has stopped and the 78-year-old
former president is getting better as he could now sit in bed.
</P>
<P>
It was unusual for his age, the doctor said, noting however
that they are not taking chances and are closely monitoring
Soeharto's condition.
</P>
<P>
"We have not thought of conducting an operation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ginting noted that he could not say when Soeharto would be
allowed to leave the hospital.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Soeharto was again rushed to the Pertamina
Hospital, where he was admitted late last month for a mild stroke.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
