<HEADLINE> Japanese Deputy FM Visits East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Deputy Foreign Minister
Machimura Nobutoha Monday met with Vice Chairman of the Indonesian
Task Force for the Implementation of the Direct Ballot in East
Timor Juwono to discuss the preparations for the August 30 ballot.
</P>
<P>
"We discussed the role of the U.N. Mission in East Timor
(UNAMET), particularly its neutrality in organizing the ballot,"
Nobutoha said in Dili, capital of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The talks also touched on the security condition after the
popular consultation, he was quoted by the Antara News Agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Juwono said that through Nobutoha's visit, Japan intended to
gather information on the latest situation in the territory,
especially during the ongoing campaign.
</P>
<P>
"We explained that the campaign, which began last August 14,
has so far run smoothly. The Japanese envoy has expressed hope
that the conducive situation would be maintained until the
completion of the ballot process," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the Japanese government's donation of 2,000 radios, Juwono
said the aid has been handed over to the UNAMET which will
distribute them to people across the territory.
</P>
<P>
He said the task force has reminded the UNAMET to distribute
the radios equally to all parties.
</P>
<P>
Nobutoha, who arrived in Dili on Sunday, is also scheduled to
meet with local government officials and religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
Under a U.N.-brokered agreement with Portugal, Indonesia agreed
to hold the autonomy ballot on August 30. The ballot will allow
the territory's people to choose whether their homeland should
become an autonomous region within Indonesia or totally
independent.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the U.N., which
still considers Portugal as the administering power of the
territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
