<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Habibie Says People Impatient to See Justice Upheld </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie Monday said he realizes that people are impatient to see
justice and law upheld.
</P>
<P>
"The people have asked the government to solve the crisis and
other problems as soon as possible," Habibie said in his state
address at the opening of the session of the House of
Representatives (DPR) for the 1999/2000 period.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, I realize the people's dissatisfaction over the
present achievements. It is natural to be dissatisfied. However,
we must also realize the heavy challenges we are facing," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the session chaired by House Speaker Harmoko, the head of
state noted that the country's political, economic, social and
judicial problems are quite complex.
</P>
<P>
"The negative impacts caused by these problems have
accumulated, leading to the present condition," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the president expressed optimism that the nation would
not fall into a worse situation.
</P>
<P>
Habibie pointed out some approaches as well as efforts which
need to be made to handle the country's problems.
</P>
<P>
To cope with these problems, integrated efforts must be carried
out carefully and gradually, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Basically, we have two options to implement change --
revolution or evolution," he said.
</P>
<P>
Revolution is quick, unpredictable and disorderly, hence risks
are great that it could cause deaths and material losses in huge
amounts, he said.
</P>
<P>
Evolution on the other hand aims to make changes in a
systematic, gradual and controlled manner and does not have the
negative side-effects of revolution, he went on to say.
</P>
<P>
"I have decided to choose evolution, that is why the efforts in
handling the country's problems have been done gradually but over
a short period of time," Habibie said.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Habibie stressed his commitment to abolishing
forms of corruption, collusion and nepotism (KKN) practices.
</P>
<P>
"There have been many KKN-related cases settled so far,
however, the people pay less attention to this effort. Instead,
perhaps most people's attention is focused on cases which contain
political nuances," the president said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not an easy task to settle KKN-related cases, because
these cases have been accumulated for a very long time, so it
takes time and needs more power support," he said.
</P>
<P>
Understanding and patience are needed in a bid to eradicate the
KKN-related cases without neglecting alertness, Habibie said,
adding that the supremacy of law should be upheld in abolishing
the cases.
</P>
<P>
Regarding current social conflicts which have erupted in some
parts of the country, Habibie said that people, particularly local
political leaders, should have the initiative to solve the
problems.
</P>
<P>
The government is determined to solve the problems peacefully
and democratically but unfortunately certain groups have selected
violence to express themselves, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to East Timor, the president said that the problem
has always harmed the interest of Indonesia in international
forums because the United Nations has not yet recognized it as an
integral part of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the government has taken the initiative to settle
the East Timor problem by offering it a wide-ranging autonomy as a
final settlement.
</P>
<P>
"If the people of East Timor refuse the special autonomy, the
government will propose to the MPR (People's Consultative
Assembly) that East Timor separate from Indonesia respectfully and
peacefully. This will be carried out if the results of the popular
consultation are in favor of that," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under a U.N.-brokered agreement with Portugal, Indonesia agreed
to hold an autonomy ballot on August 30. The ballot will allow the
territory's people to choose whether their homeland should become
an autonomous region within Indonesia or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations, which still considers Portugal as the administering power
of the territory.
</P>
<P>
Habibie is convinced that whatever decision the people of East
Timor will make, the unity and integrity of Indonesia will
continue to be maintained.
</P>
<P>
"It is a historical fact that the Indonesian people are
determined to preserve the nation's unity and state integrity," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
