<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 08:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Barak to Implement Wye: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 16 (Xinhua) -- According to a letter he
sent Prime Minister Ehud Barak over the weekend, U.S. President
Bill Clinton is pushing for a quick implementation of the Wye
agreement, local daily Haaretz reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the presidential message, following a
phone conversation between the two leaders on Thursday, added to
a flurry of U.S.pressure on Israel, including meetings conducted
by Israeli Justice Minister Yossi Beilin in Washington last week
with National Security Advisor Sandy Berger and Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
During the session, Beilin was told by the Washington power
brokers that a quick withdrawal - and release of security
prisoners - is essential to rebuild Palestinian confidence in
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The report also added the U.S. diplomatic messages concede
they know Barak wants to move the process forward, but they
express doubts that his plan to turn the third withdrawal into
part of the final status deal will win Palestinian support.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's letter was not mentioned by Barak at the cabinet
session Sunday. But the Prime Minister's Office Sunday night
confirmed that Clinton had sent a letter to Barak.
</P>
<P>
Under the Wye agreement, reached last October, Israel should
withdraw its troops from 13 percent of the West Bank in
three stages in exchange for Palestinian commitment to fight
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Barak's predecessor, hardliner Benjamin Netanyahu, carried out
the first stage last November before suspending the accord over
alleged Palestinian violations.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who said he would re-start the Wye timetable in
September, and begin the second withdrawal in October, proposed
to combine the third withdrawal with final status talks.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians have insisted the deal, if restarted in
September, should be completed by November, as laid down in the
Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian and Israeli negotiators failed on Sunday
 to break the deadlock in the peace process after meeting for
hours.
</P>
<P>
A statement from Barak's office said Sunday's meeting was
"businesslike" and that "the sides discussed all the outstanding
issues, including ways of implementing and a timetable for the
Wye Memorandum."
</P>
<P>
"On some issues agreements were reached in principle," the
statement said without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
The two sides would meet again on Tuesday, the statement
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
