<HEADLINE> Retirees Stay Away From Falun Gong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua)-- Tens of thousands of retirees in
east China's Jiangsu province have kept themselves away from Falun
Gong, avoiding being used by the cult.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu boasts over 87,000 retired cadres, who usually command
high prestige in the party and society. Over the past several
years, the Falun Gong group had tried very hard to attract these
cadres into the illegal organization.
</P>
<P>
Yu Tongbo, a retiree and former chief of the epidemic
prevention station in the city of Lianyungang, categorically
rejected Falun Gong when asked to join in for the benefit of his
health.
</P>
<P>
"I'm a Communist Party member, and educated with modern medical
science. How could I believe in Li Hongzhi's claim that the sick
can be cured just by practicing Falun Gong," Yu asked.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of retirees like Yu in the province stood firm
against Falun Gong when it was promoted and accepted by some old
cadres in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Now, former practitioners across the country see more clearly
the true nature of Falun Gong and its founder Li Hongzhi. "We were
actually fooled by Li Hongzhi," said the 34-year-old Li Dayi, of
Harbin, northeast China's Heilongjiang province.
</P>
<P>
Li Dayi began practicing Falun Gong in 1996. Last April, He
came to Beijing and took part in the April 25 illegal gathering
outside the party and government headquarters of Zhongnanhai.
</P>
<P>
Despite of his involvement, Li was not punished as he had
thought. "People around me have tried to help me in various ways.
I will break with the Falun Gong organization and contribute more
to the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
In Lanzhou City, northwest China, efforts are also being made
to help former Falun Gong practitioners break with the cult as
soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
