<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Committed to Strengthen Tourism Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Nepal is determined to make
the tourism industry more competitive, professional and
sustainable in the coming century, The Rising Nepal quoted the
chief of tourism ministry Monday.
</P>
<P>
Vijaya Kumar Gachchhadar, minister for tourism and civil
aviation, told the House of Representatives Friday that the
government has taken initiatives to expand infrastructures
associated with tourism and to develop, preserve and consolidate
the tourism heritage through publicity and other promotional
activities in the international arena.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the government has already released Rs. 18.1
million (about 260,000 U.S. dollars) for 132 programs in 51
districts through the Tourism Development Board in order to build,
improve and preserve infrastructures associated with the tourism
industry.
</P>
<P>
Gachchhadar added that a policy has been taken to make local
bodies and communities more responsible for tourism promotion
through effective coordination with governmental and
non-governmental organizations, adding that the government has
given priority to tapping geographical diversity, and promoting
national art, culture and religion.
</P>
<P>
Gachchhadar described Nepal as a unique destination for
tourists in the world because of its geographical location,
natural attraction, bio-diversity, cultural heritage and lively
arts and culture.
</P>
<P>
Tourism serves as a backbone of Nepal's economy as it is the
third largest source of foreign exchange after exports and foreign
aid. In 1997/98 fiscal year, tourism earned about 140 million U.S.
dollars and has already earned 122 million U.S. dollars in the
first eight months of the 1998/99 fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
