<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 08:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat in Egypt for Talks on Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
arrived in Egypt's Mediterranean port city of Alexandria Monday
for talks on the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was welcomed at Alexandria airport by Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa and later went into a meeting with President
Hosni Mubarak, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are expected to discuss the latest developments
of the Mideast peace process, especially on the Palestinian track,
the agency said.
</P>
<P>
They will review the efforts exerted to push the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks forward through implementing the
signed agreements, especially the Wye River peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has pledged to carry out the
overdue last two of the three-phased troop pullbacks from the West
Bank under the Wye agreement signed last October.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel have reached tentative agreement on
carrying out other aspects of the Wye accord on September 1 and
troop pullback in October.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides are still at loggerheads over when the final
phase of the withdrawal should be completed. The Palestinians have
said the Wye deal should be carried out in full by mid-November
while Israel was offering to implement the final-phase pullback by
January.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, a frequent visitor to Egypt, keeps close contact on the
Mideast peace process with Mubarak, who, as the president of the
first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with Israel, plays an
active role in mediating the peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
