<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Peace, A Must for Development in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The heads of state or government
of the Southern African Development Community (SADC) are jetting
in Maputo Monday to attend the grouping's 19th summit on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
After cheering for the dream of peace, progress and prosperity
of the region on the 19th anniversary of the establishment of the
regional organization, which falls on Tuesday, the leaders will
come back to reality and sit down seriously to talk about peace
and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The wars in Angola and the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC) are expected to dominate the political agenda of the Maputo
summit.
</P>
<P>
The continuation of armed conflicts in Angola and the DRC have
affected negatively on the economic stability, macro-economic
management and investor confidence in the directly involved
countries as well as the SADC region at large.
</P>
<P>
According to a United Nations Development Program (UNDP)
report, Angola' s 1999 human development index continues its
downward trend this year. Of the 174 countries on the list,
Angola ranks 160th, down from the 157th position last year.
</P>
<P>
Angolan Minister of Assistance and Resettlement Albino Malungo
has said that his country is in need of about 200 million U.S.
dollars in humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
Angola has accused Zambia and Mozambique of transporting arms
to the rebels of the National Union for Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA), making the originally friendly relations sour,
which also affects bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
Angola, as it is fighting its own resurgent civil war, has sent
troops to prop up the government of Congolese President Laurent
Kabila. But Angola and the Congo are among those in dire need for
food, the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) said in an
annual report on the food supply situation and crop prospects in
sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
Time and again the efforts of so many countries and even the
international community for economic progress are just annihilated
by old and new armed conflicts with all their consequences of
human suffering and destruction of property, jobs and
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, after a promising and all too brief a period, SADC's
progress has dimmed within the past year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Peace, A Must for Development in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The SADC achieved a positive economic growth rate of 1.7
percent in 1998, a quite disappointing performance compared with
the sound growth rate of 2. 7 percent in 1997 and the even more
encouraging growth of over four percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Excessive military expenditure diverts resources from human
development. According to the U.N., for the past eight years, the
UNITA rebels in Angola have raised some three to four billion U.S.
dollars through selling diamond and used most of the money to buy
arms.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the war in the Congo has created some 700,000
refugees, many of whom are fleeing to neighboring Tanzania and
Zambia, bringing much burden to the two countries.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the year-old conflict in the third largest
African country, some 85 percent of its population are living in
poverty.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the Congo recorded a negative growth of 3.5 percent
and the inflation soared up to 180 percent.
</P>
<P>
The conflicts are undermining the prospects for development in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe sent a third of the
country's army to fight for Kabila. The Zimbabwean troops are
expected to return home before Christmas this year.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's inflation was over 32 percent last year and has
averaged above 50 percent in the first half of this year. This is
far from the targeted less than 10 percent which the government
has promised international donors, who have withheld aid over poor
management and governance issues.
</P>
<P>
Striking a sharp contrast to the Angolan case, Mozambique has
been enjoying several years of peace, stability and healthy
development.
</P>
<P>
It has set an encouraging example for the region among its
reconciliation and rebuilding from the ashes of war and
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican President Joaquim Alberro Chissano said his country
is in quick recovery after 16 years of war, with economy growing
at a two-digit rate, the fastest in its history and in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The country's currency is stable and the environment for
economic growth is becoming increasingly better.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment inflow into the country has been increasing
and there has been remarkable progress in health care, power
supply and some other sectors, all thanks to the peace and
stability in the country.
</P>
<P>
The president said that he was optimistic the national economy
would enjoy further development in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The year 2000 was set as the Year of Peace and Security in
Africa at the 35th summit of the Organization of the African Unity
(OAU) in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The goal for the peace year is to see an Africa that is at
peace with itself and is able to compete on equal footing with
other regions. The need for security and stability is a
prerequisite for development and progress.
</P>
<P>
The regional leaders should recommit themselves to do
everything possible to free the region from the vicious circle of
poverty, diseases, conflicts and violence.
</P>
<P>
Hopefully, the leaders at the Maputo summit will further their
efforts to pursue peace in Angola and the Congo and stability in
the region as a whole, in a bid to usher in a peaceful and
prosperous SADC in the new millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
