<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Reveals New Method to Track Plant Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 16 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand scientists have
revealed "a world-leading technology" able to track the very
growth processes of living plants, the Dominion newspaper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The technology is the result of a unique collaboration of New
Zealand's nuclear and plant scientists, making it possible to
study plant growth processes by tracing the progress of carbon
atoms injected into plants," the Wellington-based newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Announced by HortResearch plant scientist Michael Thorpe and
the Geological and Nuclear Sciences Institute's isotope
applications manager, Peter Roberts, the sophisticated technique
allows scientists to follow the natural movement of carbohydrates
to different plant parts by tracing an injection of radioactive
carbon.
</P>
<P>
It also allows them to examine the minute sap of plant cells
down to a British billionth of a liter -- a million millionth.
</P>
<P>
"Impressively, the breakthrough extends earlier technology that
allowed scientists to follow the progress of short-lived atoms but
with longer-term tracking -- till recently, impossible," the
Dominion said.
</P>
<P>
Understanding the plant processes is a necessary step on the
way towards improved plantings, aiming at better quality crops,
less variability in produce, increased growth rates and the like,
Dr. Thorpe was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Roberts said that the carbon element allowing longer-term
tracking has previously been almost impossible to detect in the
plants.
</P>
<P>
The institute's tracer provides enormous increases in
sensitivity, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
