<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: SADC to Redouble Efforts for Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Efforts for economic growth will
get a boost at the summit of the 14-member Southern African
Development Community (SADC) which celebrates its 19th anniversary
this week.
</P>
<P>
The summit, planned for August 18 and to be preceded by grand
celebrations one day earlier, is seen as the "last-ditch effort"
by the group by the end of the century to press ahead with its
plan for economic growth and a free trade zone that has hit snags.
</P>
<P>
The "sluggish" economic growth and projected food shortage in
the region will cast a shadow on the summit, SADC officials said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the SADC region recorded a positive growth of 1.7
percent, down from the 2.7 percent of 1997 and the four percent
recorded in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The region's strongest economy, South Africa, was the main
contributor to the slump having recorded a mere 0.2 percent growth
last year. The conflict in the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC) exacerbated the situation.
</P>
<P>
"The continuation of the armed conflicts in Angola and the DRC
also impacted negatively on the economic stability, macro-economic
management and investor confidence in the directly involved
countries as well as the SADC region at large," the grouping said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The SADC secretariat predicted a growth rate of three to 3.5
percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Crop failures caused by floods and drought worsened food
shortages in the region, inflicted a cereal deficit of 2.88
million tons for the 1999/ 2000 market year, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
SADC's projected maize harvest forecast of 15.14 million tons
marked a production decline of 11 percent from 1997/98 maize
output of 17.05 million tons. The region's annual consumption is
around 19.27 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, SADC's plans to cobble a free trade agreement in the
region have suffered a serious setback, following failure by
negotiators to resolve differences on clothing and textiles.
</P>
<P>
Trade negotiators, meeting in Lusaka, Zambia earlier this
month, failed to meet their deadline for agreeing on a regional
free trade area. There was little progress made by the 11
participating countries on reducing tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Member countries like South Africa, Botswana, Namibia, Lesotho
and Swaziland had asked for more time to consider reducing tariffs
on selected products considered "sensitive".
</P>
<P>
Countries in the Southern African Customs Union (SACU) were not
 satisfied that imports "dumped" in the SADC area from places such
as Europe would not take advantage of the SADC free trade zone to
find their way into the SACU area, according to press reports.
</P>
<P>
Stimulating economic growth remained a challenge for the SADC,
said South African Foreign Minister Nkosazana Zuma.
</P>
<P>
Greater economic cooperation and adequate and effective moves
toward economic growth drew the spotlight of the just-concluded
two-day ministerial meeting, Zuma told a press conference Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting approved two drafted protocols, one on wildlife
conservation and law enforcement and the other on health, said
Zuma.
</P>
<P>
The SADC summit was expected to pave the way for the
implementation of some ratified protocols and for the ratification
of other protocols that have been worked out, Zuma added.
</P>
<P>
The summit will stress the need for consideration of whether
regional governments were ready to pool their resources to effect
rapid socio- economic development, according to conference
sources.
</P>
<P>
It was equally important for the SADC member countries to
redouble their commitment and act in a true African spirit to
ensure that the new millennium became the golden age for Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Are we ready as a region to use the full potential of all our
people without regard to race, tribal, religious and other
artificial affiliations? " one official asked.
</P>
<P>
The SADC summit will have to give an answer, said another SADC
official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Hold Urban Household Sample Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The National Bureau of
Statistics (NBS) announced today that it will hold a sample survey
on essential conditions of urban households in September.
</P>
<P>
The survey will select 150,000 households as samples in 266 big
and medium-sized cities around the country.
</P>
<P>
The questionnaire of the survey includes family size,
employment, household business, cash income, consumption
expenditure, housing, education, social security, possession of
and intent to buy durable consumer goods and preference of
consumption.
</P>
<P>
According to a NBS official, the information to be obtained
about household consumption is crucial for both the government and
enterprises to make economic policies and for operational
decisions.
</P>
<P>
Since the sample survey was first introduced 1980, it has
provided scientific basis for the government to formulate macro-
economic policies and enterprises to make management decisions.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the survey to be conducted in September
is one of the largest ever held in recent years.
</P>
<P>
NBS Director Liu Hong has sent letters to the 150,000 sampled
households to explain about the survey, which is to be conducted
jointly by the NBS, the State Development Planning Commission, the
Ministry of Education, the Ministry of Civil Affairs, the Ministry
of Labor and Social Security, the Development Research Center
under the State Council, the All-China Federation of Trade Unions
and the All-China Women's Federation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
