<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Calls for SADC/COMESA Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
called on Southern African Development Community (SADC) and Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) to merge, saying
there were currently overlaps in their functions.
</P>
<P>
Jochem Krebs, head of the EU delegation in Zambia, said all
over the world, organizations were merging and working as single
fronts for their causes.
</P>
<P>
The EU found it difficult to decide on which organization to
deal with between the two and conclude trade and economic
agreements, Krebs was quoted by Monday's Zambia Daily Mail
newspaper as saying here in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Recently, some local business organizations also indicated
their wish to see the unification of SADC and COMESA. They argued
that while SADC was more political during the fight against
colonialism, its role has become more economic like COMESA now.
</P>
<P>
They said the behind-the-scene fights going on between the two
organizations were not healthy at all as they tend to retard the
organizations from focusing on the main issue of creating wealth
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Both organizations are currently pursuing free trade among the
member states, with SADC's tariff reduction program set to start
by January 1, 2000 while COMESA's program is scheduled for October
2000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, countries in the African, Caribbean and Pacific
(ACP) grouping have said the five-year term given by the EU for
them to start trading with Europe without the preferential
treatment is too short.
</P>
<P>
The ACP countries are demanding for a 10-year period before
implementing the full free trade arrangement with EU countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
