<HEADLINE> Palestinians Key to Border Peace: U.N. Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Israel can not expect security
along its northern borders if the Palestinian refugees are
prevented from returning to their original home and are forced to
remain in Lebanon, a senior U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
Timur Goksel, political advisor of the U.N. peacekeeping
troops in south Lebanon, made the comments in an interview with
the Daily Star published on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said if there is no satisfactory outcome to the fate of the
estimated 350,000 Palestinian refugees, then they will become a
testing problem for Lebanon as well as for the Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
"Aside from the humanitarian issue, unchecked, uncontrolled and
unwanted Palestinians are not going to contribute to Israel's
security," the official added.
</P>
<P>
During a trip to Washington in July, Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak suggested that a resolution of the Palestinian refugee
dilemma be found in their host countries.
</P>
<P>
Barak's comments triggered alarm bells in Beirut where the
government adamantly rejects the possibility of settling the
Palestinians permanently in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese authorities fear that the move would tip the delicate
sectarian balance that guarantees the peaceful coexistence
between Muslims and Christians in post-civil war Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
