<HEADLINE> Dubai Seizes 1 Ton of Drugs in 7 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The police department of
Dubai, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), has seized more than one
ton of drugs in 167 cases in the first seven months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,008 kilograms narcotics, including hashish, heroin,
opium, marijuana, were confiscated in the 167 cases involving 246
criminals, according to statistics from the Dubai Police Criminal
Investigation Department.
</P>
<P>
Col. Khalfan Khalfan, director of the department, stressed
the importance of coordination among different emirates of the
UAE in fighting drug trafficking, the Gulf News daily reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This constant coordination has been made more effective after
the organization of the Drug Control Committee headed by Dhahi
Tamim, the Dubai Police chief," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also called for closer cooperation among drug control
departments in the world to help monitor and stop inter-state drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Due to its important position as a regional trade center,
"Dubai has been made a transit station for drug smugglers," he
explained.
</P>
<P>
"The amount entering the country is far more than the demand
of consumers, but traffickers always seek ways to distribute to
other countries in the region via Dubai," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
