<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's First Exchange Fund Notes Listed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's first batch of
Exchange Fund Notes (EFNs) was listed Monday at the Stock Exchange
of Hong Kong, offering retail investors an attractive and reliable
investment opportunity.
</P>
<P>
Issued by the Hong Kong Monetary Authority, the 57 issues of
EFNs listed Monday were worth 34 billion HK dollars (4.36 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Economists called the listing a milestone in the development of
Hong Kong's debt market, as Hong Kong has long attached a
disproportionate reliance on the banking and equity markets.
</P>
<P>
The EFNs will help channel the savings of the community into
productive investment and improve the efficiency of Hong Kong's
financial intermediation, they noted.
</P>
<P>
They said the EFNs attract a yield higher than that for U.S.
dollar Treasury securities of corresponding maturity. Interests
income from holding the EFNs will be exempt from profits tax and
trading in the paper will be exempt from stamp duty.
</P>
<P>
The Exchange Fund papers are fully backed by Hong Kong's
foreign reserves. For every 780 HK dollars worth of EFNs, there is
100 U.S. dollars held in the Exchange Fund.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Hong Kong and Hong Kong Monetary
Authority signed the agreement on the listing on July 19, this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
