<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Major Snag to Growth: Kenyan Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Agricultural Minister
Musalia Mudavadi has said the country's leading obstacle to
economic development today is HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
He said Sunday that his government spends a lot of resources to
curb the spread of the disease at the expense of other development
programs, the East African Standard reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The minister mentioned the increasing number of AIDS orphans
and called for a collective responsibility among all stakeholders
in a bid to control the disease.
</P>
<P>
It is said that to date there are 600,000 AIDS orphans in this
east African country.
</P>
<P>
Mudavadi expressed his worry that students both in primary and
secondary school have now fallen prey to the AIDS scourge.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the National AIDS Control Program said there will be
400 HIV/AIDS-related deaths a day by 2005 unless Kenyans are to
protect themselves against the scourge.
</P>
<P>
According to surveillance, HIV prevalence in Kenya in the last
eight years has increased from 3.1 percent to 14 percent by the
end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Godfrey Baltazar of the National AIDS Control Program noted
that those infected are people between the age of 15 and 49 and
the impact on the economy was reduction of labor forces by 10
years.
</P>
<P>
Since the first AIDS case was discovered in Kenya in 1984,
500,000 Kenyans have died of the disease. It is expected that
another 200,000 would die from AIDS-related complications by the
end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
