<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banking Restructuring Causes Rupiah Fall: Habibie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie said Monday that problems in the banking restructurization
program and external influences have caused the rupiah
depreciation against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
"External influences and problems in banking restructurization
has caused the rupiah depreciation, which has been down to around
8,000 rupiah currently," said Habibie in a state address when
opening the session of the House of Representatives (DPR) for the
1999/2000 period here Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, the head of state did not clearly mention the current
Bank Bali scandal which allegedly involved some ranking government
officials as stated by former Bank Bali Director Rudy Ramli over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The scandal has caused a rupiah depreciation from the
6,000-level to the current 7,000-level.
</P>
<P>
Publicly-listed Bank Bali and the Indonesian Bank Restructuring
Agency (IBRA) had allegedly committed a criminal act which also
involved a member of the ruling Golkar Party's central executive
board.
</P>
<P>
Bank Bali allegedly paid Golkar Deputy Treasurer Setyo Novanto
and other businessmen related to Golkar some 550 billion rupiah
(80.86 million dollars) in commission for recovering 904.6 billion
rupiah (about 133 million U.S. dollars) in inter-bank credits.
</P>
<P>
Facing the rupiah's depreciation, Habibie said, the government
has been trying to solve the problems in the banking sector
wholeheartedly.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Habibie stressed the importance of the need for
special attention to the management of the state budget in the
future, as national spending may likely increase.
</P>
<P>
"Our state budget for development programs is adequate but for
the years to come national spending may continue to increase
because the country will pay the interest of foreign loans used in
the recapitalization program," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government has also launched the restructurization program
in state companies in an effort to lessen the country's dependence
on foreign assistance.
</P>
<P>
By listing 49 percent of state companies' stake in the stock
market, the government hopes it could reap 91 billion U.S. dollars
for fiscal year 1999/2000 ending March 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
"In the long run the money can be used to repay the foreign
loan," Habibie said.
</P>
<P>
The government, he said, should also raise the national income
from tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
If the country is able to increase the ratio of tax revenue
from the current 11 percent to 16 percent in 2004, the national
income will rise to 5 billion to 7 billion U.S. dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
If the national income increases, the salary of civil workers,
military personnel and policemen will be up as well, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
