<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Olympic Organiser, Company Settle Band Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- An international marching band
will perform at next year's Olympic opening ceremony after Sydney
Olympic organisers and the band promoter settled the long-running
dispute outside court in Sydney Monday.
</P>
<P>
The deal, reached by Sydney Organising Committee for Olympic
Games (SOCOG) and World Projects Corporation (WPC), came during an
adjournment just over an hour into a hearing of the case brought
by WPC against SOCOG, at New South Wales state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will see WPC put together a revised band
comprising more Australians, fewer Americans and youngsters from
18 other countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the SOCOG will pay extra 1 million
Australian dollars (660,000 U.S. dollars), which also covers legal
costs for WPC, for the revised band.
</P>
<P>
Australian Olympics Minister Michael Knight said the deal was
satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
"While the negotiated compromise is not what either side would
ideally prefer, it is now closer to the concept of a world band,"
Knight said.
</P>
<P>
The number of young Australians will increase by around 400 and
they will be the largest group represented.
</P>
<P>
"WPC has taken full responsibility for reducing the number of
Americans, maintaining the Japanese numbers and recruiting other
young musicians from around the world," Knight added.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed last week on a more international band
involving musicians from about 20 countries from all continents
instead of the original comprising of Americans, Australians and
Japanese.
</P>
<P>
SOCOG had offered to pay WPC extra 800,000 Australian dollars (
528,000 U.S. dollars) to compile the bigger band but the company
was asking for 1.2 million Australian dollars (792,000 U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Since the SOCOG changed its decision on the comprising of the
band in June, WPC had pressed ahead with court action against
SOCOS on the band dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
