<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 06:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Confirms Freeze on Unskilled Labor From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Untied Arab Emirates
(UAE) has confirmed a freeze on unskilled manpower from India and
Pakistan, ending weeks of rumor and speculation on this issue.
</P>
<P>
"Fresh recruitment of manual workers from the two countries
has been frozen," the Gulf News daily quoted an official from the
Ministry of Labor as saying on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The freeze on manual labor was due to an increasing number of
jobless manual workers in the UAE from the two countries, said
Mohammed Issa Al Suwaidi, undersecretary for Labor Affairs at the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
He said surplus workers from the two countries were extremely
high compared with that of other nationalities, adding that the
ministry's policies were based on demand and supply.
</P>
<P>
"Studies show a huge surplus in the numbers of manual workers
from these two countries and suggest that demand is less than the
supply," said the official.
</P>
<P>
The UAE must regulate the labor market by giving opportunities
to jobless people here, instead of bringing in new recruits, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Rumors of a ban began circulating last month, and the
situation was further confused by reports in India that the UAE
had placed a blanket ban on all recruitment.
</P>
<P>
Al Suwaidi confirmed that the ban did not apply to
professional or skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
"Skilled workers who submit certificates showing academic
qualifications will be granted employment visas," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Skilled people are still coming from these two and other
countries, and their entry is allowed at any time," he added.
</P>
<P>
The UAE is a large market for foreign labors. Among its
current population of around 2.7 million, two-thirds are
expatriates, notably Indians and Pakistanis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
