<HEADLINE> West Should Apologize to Africans Over AIDS: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 16 (Xinhua) -- As new evidence suggests that the
first person to die of AIDS could have been in the United States
of America in the early 1960s, the Western world should apologize
to Africans for wrongfully blaming them for the scourge, a WHO
official has said.
</P>
<P>
Ebrahim Samba, regional director for Africa of the World Health
 Organization (WHO), Sunday told the daily Herald that the Center
For Disease Control in Atlanta, the United States, had proof that
the first patient died between 1961 and 1962 of a "rare disease".
</P>
<P>
The person's tissues were kept and revisited recently. HIV
immuno bodies were found in the frozen tissues, the Herald
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"All the bad things are said to emerge from Africa, while all
the good come from the West. The West should, therefore, send a
letter of apology to Africa for being wrongfully blamed," said
Samba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
