<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Libraries Urged to Exploit IT Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Energy,
Communications and Multimedia Minister Leo Moggie Monday asked
libraries in the country to upgrade the conventional library
services by fully exploiting the latest information technology
(IT) available.
</P>
<P>
Libraries should plan and develop knowledge and information
products and services to fulfill the changing needs of library
users and to support the development of the National Information
and Knowledge Infrastructure, he said when opening a three-day
Conference and Workshop on Digital Library here.
</P>
<P>
The conference, themed "Global Access and National Identity"
and jointly organized by the National Library, the Librarians'
Association of Malaysia and University Putra Malaysia, is held in
conjunction with August being the national reading month.
</P>
<P>
Leo Moggie said tremendous amount of information are being
published everyday, especially via the World Wide Web, and
libraries therefore face the challenge of how to systematically
manage and preserve digital resources available on CD-ROMs, VCDs,
DVDs and online databases.
</P>
<P>
Multimedia digital libraries in the next millennium need to be
effective repositories of knowledge and information by ensuring
easy, quick and reliable access to global multimedia resources,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Libraries of the future would be able to provide not only
24-hour online service to the global community, but also function
as a gateway to digital information resources and as one-stop
knowledge and information centers through proper utilization of
communications infrastructure, he said, adding this will expedite
the acculturation of IT and knowledge among Malaysians.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian National Library has recently acquired a
digitization system at a cost of 300,000 ringgit (about 79,000
U.S. dollars) to convert publications to digital format. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
