<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Trade News in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of major trade news
in China between August 9 and 15:
</P>
<P>
-- China's central bank announced here last Monday that foreign
banks in Shanghai and Shenzhen are now allowed to engage in yuan-
based business in more localities, and some restrictions
concerning the scale of such business have been eased as well.
</P>
<P>
The decision has been welcomed by both domestic and overseas
bankers because it provides opportunities for foreign bankers to
increase activities in China and for Chinese banks to improve
their competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
-- A national fair on high-tech achievements will be held in
the coastal city of Qingdao in east China's Shandong Province on
September 7-10.
</P>
<P>
-- China's Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (
MOFTEC) recently revoked the licenses of two training centers for
their substandard service to train Chinese laborers working
overseas.
</P>
<P>
-- More than 20 multinational corporations will participate in
the upcoming '99 China Fair for International Investment and Trade,
slated for September 8-12 in the eastern port city of Xiamen,
Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
-- China reported an export growth rate of 7.5 percent in July,
a second consecutive month of positive growth this year, prompting
experts to make a more favorable prediction of trade figures for
the coming months. Report from the General Administration of
Customs on Thursday shows that the export volume in July reached
17.34 billion US dollars-worth.
</P>
<P>
-- The China United Coal-Bed Methane Corp. Ltd. (CUCBM) and
SABA Petroleum Inc. of the United States signed a contract here
last Friday to jointly explore methane resources in south China's
Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
-- China will offer 69 projects of building materials sector,
involving 15.78 billion US dollars, for overseas investors in a
coming national fair.
</P>
<P>
-- A specialized export credit insurance company is under
planning as a way to encourage China's exports.
</P>
<P>
-- Invitations have been sent out and preparations are in full
swing for the first Trade and Investment Exposition of the Pacific
Economic Cooperation Council (PECC), which will be held September
14-18 in the north China port city of Tianjin. 
</P>
