<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, U.S. Ink Accord on Joint Anti-missile Defense Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Japan and the United States on
Monday signed an agreement committing the two countries to conduct
joint technical research on a U.S.-proposed anti-missile defense
system.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura and U.S. Ambassador
to Japan Thomas Foley signed and exchanged diplomatic notes on the
Theater Missile Defense (TMD) system.
</P>
<P>
The agreement incorporates the areas of cooperation of the two
countries, including infrared sensors to detect enemy missiles.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo and Washington agreed last December to start this year
the joint research on the TMD, which is designed to protect the U.
S. and its allies from incoming ballistic missiles flying within a
3,000-kilometer radius.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese cabinet gave final approval to the TMD project, a
five-to-six-year program, last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will share an expected 50-60 billion yen (439
million to 526 million U.S. dollars) cost for the research, with
Japan shouldering between 20 billion yen (175 million dollars) and
30 billion yen (263 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
