<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Marks 85th Anniversary of Canal Opening </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Panama marked the 85th
anniversary of the opening of the Panama Canal on Sunday, the last
anniversary under U.S. control.
</P>
<P>
Colombian President Andres Pastrana, Costa Rican President
Miguel Angel Rodriguez, Mexican Foreign Secretary Rosario Green
and Cesar Gaviria, secretary general of the Organization of
American States, joined Panamanian President Ernesto Perez
Balladares at the unveiling ceremony of a memorial plaque at Gatun
Locks, near the Atlantic entrance to the canal.
</P>
<P>
Panama's fight for sovereignty over the canal had been backed
by the whole of Latin America, said Rodriguez when addressing the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Later in the day, foreign ministers of Colombia, Costa Rica and
Panama signed the "Panama Declaration," which reaffirms Panama's
sovereignty over the canal and predicts a social and economic
improvement of Panama with the forthcoming regaining of the canal
zone.
</P>
<P>
The canal will be controlled by Panama starting on December 31,
as agreed in 1977 treaties between then U.S. President Jimmy
Carter and Panama's then military leader Gen. Omar Torrijos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
