<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Govt Job-Creating Move Proves Effective </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The move was aimed at easing the unemployment crisis and
boosting economic activity following a two-year recession.
</P>
<P>
Budget Bureau Director Sawasdiparp Kanthatham was quoted as
saying that as of July 31, the five ministries and seven
departments involved in the program reported that a total of
44,015 jobs had been created for educated job-seekers.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government expects to create a total of 86,000 jobs
for educated people to cover those hit by the economic crisis and
new graduates.
</P>
<P>
The government also expects to create another 400,000 unskilled
jobs, mainly in rural areas, to cope with the return of labor from
Bangkok and the big cities. The emphasis is on irrigation, small
infrastructure and community enhancement, which will be given more
than 20 billion baht (541 million U.S. dollars) by the program.
</P>
<P>
The program is mainly financed by a 53-billion baht (1.4
billion dollars) loan from Japan's Miyazawa Fund, which was set up
in late 1998 in the wake of the Asian financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
