<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Stone Statue Discovered in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A headless stone statue dating
back to the Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368) has been discovered in the
downtown area of this Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists believe the statue is of Zhen Wu (Xuan Wu), an
immortal worshipped by Taoists.
</P>
<P>
They say it is one of the very few Yuan stone statues so far
discovered, and the only inscribed one of Zhen Wu.
</P>
<P>
The seated figure, carved out of a single piece of stone, is 1.
67 m tall and 0.76 m wide. In his right hand, Zhen Wu holds a
sword, and his left hand is placed on one knee.
</P>
<P>
The inscription identifies the designer and the place it was
carved.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists say the statue is of great value for the study
and authentication of Yuan stone carvings, despite the fact that
the head is missing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
