<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Revamp Local Government Institutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government will
examine the recommendations by a commission of inquiry and take
necessary steps to reform local government institutions, the
Presidential Secretariat said Monday.
</P>
<P>
President Kumaratunga appointed the Commission of Inquiry on
Local Government Reforms in February, 1998, the second of its kind
in the country. The first is the Choksy Commission set up in 1953.
</P>
<P>
The appointment was due to public agitation for reforms as it
was considered that the system of local government prevailing in
the country required reorganization, the secretariat said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The commission has provided opportunities to the public to
submit views in writing or give oral evidence, it said.
</P>
<P>
The commission handed over its report to the president last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
During its inquiry, the commission examined 331 memoranda and
heard the evidence of 237 persons. Several seminars and workshops
were also organized to consult the heads of local authorities and
those involved in local government administration.
</P>
<P>
The commission also examined several aspects of local
administration pertaining to legal affairs, institutional
arrangements, the electoral system and the functioning of wards
and standing committees.
</P>
<P>
It also examined the formulation of national policy, the
functions of local authorities and the election and functions of
mayors and chairmen of local bodies.
</P>
<P>
The commission specially looked into financial management of
local institutions and have come up with proposals for significant
changes in local administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
