<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Universal Postal Union Says Postal Service Faced With Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Postal reforms should be placed
under government control and the recent trend of privatization in
some countries should not be encouraged, according to Thomas
Leavey, director general of the Universal Postal Union (UPU).
</P>
<P>
The UPU chief made the remarks during an exclusive interview
with Xinhua at the UPU headquarters in the Swiss capital of Berne
before he left for Beijing to attend the 22nd Universal Postal
Congress scheduled from August 23 to September 15.
</P>
<P>
He said that the congress in Beijing is an extremely important
event for the worldwide postal community at the turn of the
century when postal services face many new challenges.
</P>
<P>
The UPU chief stressed that while it is necessary for postal
services to adjust to technological developments, they should not
forget their commitment to fulfill the public service obligations
mandated by their governments.
</P>
<P>
Their role in the development of communications is vital, not
only as a means of exchanging information, but also as a way of
maintaining and promoting social cohesion, he said.
</P>
<P>
As competition in postal services is becoming more and more
intense, Leavey said, the UPU is trying to help developing
countries, providing them with 2.5 million Swiss francs (about 1.6
million U.S. dollars) from the UPU budget for technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
"The 49 least developed countries get the priority," he said,
adding the UPU also seeks more assistance from other international
agencies such as the World Bank, regional development banks, and
the United Nations Development Program.
</P>
<P>
"We have made an effort to try to improve the infrastructure of
developing countries," the UPU chief said. "That of course would
help improve the quality of service." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
