<HEADLINE> Private Schools Thrive in Guangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 16 (Xinhua) -- When night falls in this
capital of south China's Guangdong Province, thousands of people
do not hurry home; instead they rush to night schools.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all these schools are privately funded and provide
education from kindergarten to higher-learning courses.
</P>
<P>
Private schools first appeared in the city in 1979. Now, there
are 516 private kindergartens, 65 private high schools and over 50
private higher-learning institutes. It is said that some 2.6
million people have been trained in these schools so far.
</P>
<P>
Courses offered by these private schools are very market-
oriented, which is one of the main differences between private
schools and public schools in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, when the city became one of the first
trailblazers in China to open for overseas investment, there was a
big demand for people proficient in foreign languages. As a result,
private schools soon took on the role of offering language courses.
</P>
<P>
Then, in the early 1990s accountancy became a hot subject.
Private schools easily adjusted to offer related courses.
</P>
<P>
So far, computer, MBA and English courses are the most popular
choices in private schools. But more varieties of courses are
springing up, as people now have more money in their pockets. They
include dancing and body-building.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
