<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin has called on the whole
country to emancipate mind and seek truth from facts to push
forward the reform and development of China's State-owned
enterprises (SOEs).
</P>
<P>
Jiang, also general secretary of the Communist Party of China (
CPC) Central Committee and chairman of the Central Military
Commission, made the call during an August 10-15 inspection of
some SOEs in northeast China's Liaoning Province, a traditional
heavy industrial base.
</P>
<P>
The president termed the SOE reform and development a crucial
and cross-century strategic target under the current international
and domestic situation, which was set forth at the 15th National
CPC Congress and must be well carried out.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the major issue will be put on top of the
agenda at the Fourth Plenum of the 15th CPC Central Committee,
which will be held in autumn this year.
</P>
<P>
-- The fundamental starting point in the campaign against Falun
Gong is to further maintain the country's stability and unity so
as to focus efforts on its opening up and reforms and
modernization drive, says a commentary of the paper.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- China's top lawmaker Li Peng recently spoke highly of the
current "Three Stresses" campaign, an educational drive among
Party officials to stress theoretical study, political
consciousness and healthy trends among the people.
</P>
<P>
Li, chairman of the National People's Congress Standing
Committee, emphasized the leading role of the Communist Party of
China (CPC) in the work of the country's top legislative body.
</P>
<P>
-- People from all walks of life continue their criticism of
Falun Gong and its founder Li Hongzhi.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- State-owned enterprises in northeast China's three provinces
made restructuring breakthroughs during the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The three provinces have witnessed the biggest progress in
reducing deficit and increasing profits since substantial reforms
were launched several years ago.
</P>
<P>
-- China voiced its strong displeasure and firm opposition to
the U.S. government for allowing the Dalai Lama to visit the
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
