<HEADLINE> Manila Declares Moratorium on New Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank
suspended indefinitely the issuance of new bank licenses over the
weekend to further encourage mergers and acquisitions in the
industry, The Philippine Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the Central Bank Governor Rafael Buenaventura
as saying that "we have frozen all applications for new bank
licenses," and the central bank would assess which areas
nationwide are "overbanked or underbanked."
</P>
<P>
On top of the moratorium, the Central Bank also wants to impose
an increase in the minimum capitalization requirement for new
banks for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
Banks have to fully comply with the mandatory 20 percent to 60
percent hike in capital by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
"As a rule, I would like to see people buying existing banks.
They should merge first before the suspension is lifted,"
Buenaventura elaborated, noting that "in fact, a lot of bargains"
could be found presently at the system.
</P>
<P>
Buenaventura disclosed that the Central Bank is even planning
to grant incentives to banks expanding operations in places which
lack banking services.
</P>
<P>
The governor said it was imperative for banks to consolidate to
survive the tightening competition and the irreversible trend of
globalization as these demand higher capital and resources.
</P>
<P>
He had earlier predicted that as a result of the tighter
capital build-up program which he plans to increase some more in
2001, around three to six mega-banks would dominate the business
with the smaller ones turning as "niche players" over the long
term.
</P>
<P>
It is also the objective to the new governor to stimulate the
creation of at least three all-Filipino regional banks within his
six-year tenure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
