<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Map Legal System to Amplify Price Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua)-- China's State Development
Planning Commission (SDPC) plans to establish a "relatively
complete" legal system for price regulation by the end of next
year, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The system, based on rules and regulations on price management,
price control and supervision and investigation into pricing work,
is to be set up on the basis of the Price Law.
</P>
<P>
"In line with the new economic situation, the SDPC will adopt
policies and draft regulations to encourage the expansion of
domestic market demand," an official of the commission was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Using the pricing lever to promote economic growth is very
important in the current market-oriented economy, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
The commission is currently drafting a managerial procedure on
the price of low-cost homes for urban dwellers on medium or low
incomes, in a bid to speed up the construction of this type of
housing.
</P>
<P>
Rules on the prices of medical services are also in the
pipeline to serve the ongoing medical care reform, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
The SDPC is drafting rules to regulate the fee-collecting
activities of certain intermediate organizations so as to achieve
"orderly competition". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
