<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volunteers Fight Desertification in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Sino-Japanese non-governmental
organizations have launched a joint campaign to fight
desertification in China, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
About 200 volunteers from the two countries traveled to north
China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region on Sunday. In three to
four days there, they will plant trees, hold lectures on ecology
and conduct science promotion surveys.
</P>
<P>
Nearly one-third of China's land is endangered by
desertification and 2,460 square kilometers of land becomes desert
every year, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was jointly organized by the China Youth
Development Foundation with the Japan Desert Afforestation
Practice Association.
</P>
<P>
It aims at soliciting financial aid from international
community to help the areas jeopardized by desertification in
China to obtain sustainable development while protecting the
environment.
</P>
<P>
A fund to support the campaign has already been set up by the
China Youth Development Foundation. Non-governmental organizations
will be set up in Japan to help raise funds and publicize the
campaign, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
