<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Navy Seizes 2 Vessels Suspected of Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Navy on Sunday
night seized two suspicious vessels off the northwestern coast,
naval officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The officials said the two vessels were suspected to have been
engaged in smuggling people or goods between northwestern Sri
Lanka and southern India.
</P>
<P>
The first vessel, a fibre glass dingy, was detected about 11
p.m. off Talaimannar, over 300 kilometers north of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The three Tamils aboard were returning home after transporting
24 Tamil refugees to India, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The next vessel was an Indian boat which the navy discovered 20
minutes later and seized it together with nine persons, three of
whom were males while the others were women and children.
</P>
<P>
The second boat also carried a cargo of textiles.
</P>
<P>
The two boats and those detained have been handed over to the
Talaimannar police for investigation.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka, plagued by a 16-year-old ethnic civil war, has been
keeping close watch over the sea off its north and northwest to
curb the smuggling activities of Tamil rebels who demand a
separate homeland in the country's north and east. 
</P>
</TEXT>
