<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Fails to Anticipate Progress of Thailand, Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The National Olympic Committee
of Indonesia (KONI) admitted it failed to anticipate the rapid
progress made by Thailand and Malaysia at the Southeast Asian (SEA)
Games which finished on Sunday, The Indonesian Observer reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The miscalculation allowed the two countries to trample over
the Indonesian contingent. Failure to achieve the team's medal
targets was attributed to the federation's ignorance of the
strength of the other two teams. Consequently, chances of gold
simply evaporated.
</P>
<P>
One week before the departure for Brunei, chief de mission M.
Hindarto and his aide Imron ZS were still optimistic that the
contingent would garner somewhere between 60 and 70 gold medals.
However, the final result was a mere 44.
</P>
<P>
Rudolf Warouw, KONI vice chairman, said the failure should be
shared collectively, and is not a question of blame.
</P>
<P>
"A scapegoat is not needed. What is more important is how to
prepare for the Sydney Olympics and the 2001 SEA Games in Kuala
Lumpur," he said.
</P>
<P>
KONI will immediately call the sporting federations together
for consultation and evaluation of the athletes' performance in
each event, he added.
</P>
<P>
The results of the 20th SEA Games indicates Indonesia is now
lagging behind in athletics, swimming, cycling, shooting,
billiards and bowling, which are events requiring skill rather
than judgement.
</P>
<P>
"We should be making more of an effort in our talent scouting
exercises, because as long as we remain unable to catch up in
those sports, and they are sports which contain a huge number of
gold medals, we are doomed to failure," he said.
</P>
<P>
Athletics and swimming events at the Brunei SEA Games provided
a total of 78 gold medals of which Thailand harvested 33, Malaysia
19, while Indonesia managed only 10.
</P>
<P>
"KONI should now give priority to athletics and swimming,"
Warouw said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990816.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Fails to Retain Its Position at SEA Champion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia failed to retain its
position as overall champion in the 20th Southeast Asian (SEA)
Games ended in Brunei on Sunday, according to the Antara News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia came out third after Thailand and Malaysia collecting
only 44 golds. Thailand won 65 while Malaysia 57 gold medals.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time Malaysia beat Indonesia in gold medal
collection since the first SEA Games in Kuala Lumpur in 1977.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia was the only country who failed to win any medal from
the 21 sport branches competing in the two yearly game.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has been overall champion three times while Indonesia
nine times.
</P>
<P>
Following is the medal tally of the games (tabulated under
country, gold, silver and bronze medals):
</P>
<P>
1. Thailand 65  48  56
</P>
<P>
2. Malaysia 57  45  42
</P>
<P>
3. Indonesia  44  43  58
</P>
<P>
4. Singapore  23  28  45
</P>
<P>
5. Philippines  19  27  40
