<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serena Williams Wins Acura Classic Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Serena Williams went one
step further than her elder sister Venus did a week ago --
defeating the current world No. 1 in the semifinals and winning a
tournament.
</P>
<P>
One day after knocking off top-ranked Martina Hingis, Serena
Williams cruised to her third title of the season today with a 6-1,
6-4 victory over Julie Halard-Decugis of France in the final of
the $520,000 Acura Classic here.
</P>
<P>
Seeded sixth, Serena Williams broke her French opponent twice
in each set as she moved within one of matching Venus' four 1999
victories. The younger Williams won $80,000.
</P>
<P>
With her victory today, Serena Williams will move up two spots
to No. 9 when the new WTA rankings are released Monday. That will
equal Serena's previous career-high ranking, which she held for a
three-week stretch in April.
</P>
<P>
Playing her first event since the French Open, Serena Williams
dropped only one set in five matches. She improved her season
record to 31-6, including 24-3 on hardcourts.
</P>
<P>
The unseeded Halard-Decugis was in her fifth finals appearance
this season after upsetting Davenport in the semifinals yesterday.
The Frenchwoman's performance this week will allow her to leap
five spots to a career-high No. 11 in next week's rankings.
</P>
<P>
Halard-Decugis, 28, continued one of the great comeback stories
in recent memory. She did not compete for more than a year due to
wrist and knee injuries before returning to action in January 1998
and winning two tournaments last season. This year, she has won
two titles and finished runner-up in three others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
